<HEAD>Rose Bet on Games Beginning in '85, Investigator Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with more details from report. No pickup.
A version moved on sports wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY78</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD BLUM</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 and
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BEN WALKER</NOTE>
<NOTE>AP Sports Writers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> bet on <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> games over a three-year span beginning in 1985, and once accumulated a $ 400,000 gambling debt over a three-month period, the sport's investigator concludes in a 225-page report released Monday. The report by baseball investigator <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dowd </PERSON> was publicly released Monday by a state judge who had kept it private until after he ruled on <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>'s request for a temporary restraining order. `` Between May and July 1987, Rose bet ... $ 2,000 per game on baseball, including <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> games,'' the report said. <LOCATION> Hamilton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Common Pleas Judge <PERSON> Norbert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nadel </PERSON> released the report Monday under pressure from the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which said he had no reason to keep it sealed. <PERSON> Nadel </PERSON> on Sunday granted <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>'s request to block a hearing that was scheduled for Monday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with baseball Commissioner <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> <PERSON> Giamatti </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>'s manager, could be banned from the game for life if it is determined that he bet on the <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dowd </PERSON>'s report said there was much evidence that he did, although it noted that <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> has denied under oath he ever bet on major league baseball. `` The accumulated testimony of witnesses, together with documentary evidence and telephone records, reveal extensive betting activity by <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> with professional baseball and, in particular, <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> games, during the 1985, 1986 and 1987 seasons,'' <PERSON> Dowd </PERSON> said in the report. The report quotes <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> associate <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Janszen </PERSON> as saying `` within a three-month period of time, <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> was in debt over $ 400,000 to the bookie in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' It does not indicate if the debt was due to baseball debts or wagers on other sports. Rose bet 52 times on the <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> _ and won 29 _ from April 8-July 5, 1987, according to gambling records cited in <PERSON> Dowd </PERSON>'s report. <PERSON> Dowd </PERSON> cited telephone records and betting slips supplied by <PERSON> Janszen </PERSON>, who claims to have run bets for <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, as supporting evidence. He also said that evidence supports the testimony of bookmaker <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>, who claims he took perhaps more than $ 1 million in bets on behalf of Rose over a two-year period. `` The evidence revealed that in order to protect his stature as one of the most famous baseball players in major league history, <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> employed middlemen to place bets for him with bookmakers and at the raetrack and to pay gambling losses and collect gambling winnings, thereby concealing his gambling activity,'' <PERSON> Dowd </PERSON> wrote. Despite the $ 400,000 debt, the report said, <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> had been successful early in the 1987 season in bets with <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>'s chief accuser <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, an associate of <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>, recalled being told by <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> during the 1987 season that he was `` getting murdered'' by <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> on baseball. `` <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> stated that <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> advised him that <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> had him ` hooked' for ` about seventy-five thousand,' `` the report said. In addition, the report says that <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> owned half of a $ 47,646 Pik-Six ticket at <LOCATION> Turfway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> on April 6, 1989. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gioiosa </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>'s former housemate, `` falsely represented to the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> that he was the sole winner,'' the report said. <PERSON> Gioiosa </PERSON> has been indicted for that and <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> is under investigation by a federal grand jury in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>. After the <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> beat <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> 5-3 Monday night, <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> was asked if he believed the report was balanced. `` I can give you an outline,'' he said. `` There's 225 pages and there's two paragraphs positive about me. It's such a biased report it's unbelievable. But we will face that because there's not a thing we can do about it.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stachler </PERSON>, a Rose attorney, said he was not bothered that the report was made public. He declined further comment.
