<HEAD>Helmsley Tax Evasion Trial Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hotel queen <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> went on trial Monday on federal charges that she evaded income taxes by disguising about $ 4 million in renovations to her mansion as business expenses. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>, 68, watched as potential jurors were questioned about their impartiality and how much they knew about the highly publicized case. By late afternoon, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> had interviewed 18 potential jurors and dismissed four. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said he would screen the pool of 160 prospective jurors this week and allow attorneys to make their final peremptory challenges July 5 before opening arguments. One man was excused because he said he was upset about being asked his salary and because he was mad at judges in general for allowing the flag to be burned, referring to last week's <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision. The other potential jurors who were dismissed were a man who had read an article about Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> in Monday's <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>; an accountant who once did work for a company that will be named at trial; and a man who said he was angry with the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for the way it handled a tax problem. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> was named in a 47-count indictment in April 1988 with her husband, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>, and two former <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> executives. The Helmsleys, who head a $ 5 billion hotel and real estate empire, were accused of evading personal income taxes by concealing about $ 4 million in renovations to their <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, mansion as business expenses. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>, 80, has been found incompetent to stand trial because of his memory lapses. The other defendants, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Licari </PERSON>, are charged with helping create bogus invoices to make it appear the renovations on the 28-room mansion were tax-deductible improvements on business properties. Many potential jurors said they knew the <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION> from media reports and Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> from advertisements for her hotels that portray her as the `` queen'' of Helmsley-owned hotels. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> allowed jurors to remain in the pool if they said they could be impartial. One answer given by a 28-year-old architect's intern prompted a cold stare from Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>. The juror was asked what he knew of the Helmsleys from the media. `` He's old and feeble, and <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> runs things,'' the man said.
