<HEAD>Germany Moving Against Firm in Iran Chemical Weapons Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The West German government is taking action against a German firm that has arranged the sale to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of chemicals that make poison gas, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials confirmed Monday night. The officials said Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> discussed the sale with Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> during <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>'s visit to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last week. `` We've been very happy'' with the German response, said one official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Both officials said they did not have precise details of just what the <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> government was doing in the case. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said in Tuesday editions that a <LOCATION> Dusseldorf </LOCATION> firm, which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials did not identify, had acted as a broker in arranging the sale to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of hundreds of tons of thionyl chloride, a chemical that can be used to make mustard gas, by an Indian manufacturer. The bulk of the chemicals was said not to have been delivered. Iranian troops were the targets of several gas attacks by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the eight-year war between those two countries. Last winter, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials accused German firms of helping <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> built a plant that could be used to produce chemical weapons, though <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> insisted the plant would be used for pharmaceuticals. In response, the <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> government has proposed legislation to stiffen export controls and penalties for violating them.
