<HEAD>Judge Again Extends Sealing Order On Unisys Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Monday extended a sealing order on several documents seized by government agents who were looking for evidence that <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> bought information to help it win defense contracts. Judge <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> extended until July 27 the sealing order affecting documents taken from the offices of <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> employees <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Elfering </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Geiger </PERSON>. The three were among those searched on June 14, 1988, in a nationwide sweep by federal agents investigating possible bribery of public officials, conspiracy and fraud in the defense department's procurement system A number of documents relating to searches of the <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> facilities of <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> have been sealed at the government's request since June 16, 1988. Other documents have been made public since the initial sealing order was filed. On May 17, the court had extended the sealing order for several of the documents until June 26, when the government had believed that its need for continued sealing of the documents would end. However, because of scheduling conflicts, the government moved to extend the order until July 27 because it had been unable to proceed as quickly as expected.
