<HEAD>Those Accused of Killing Caribbean Leader Wait and Wait</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly six years after an army firing squad killed Prime Minister <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> after a military coup, 17 people accused in the slaying still await a final verdict. <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON>'s death in a factional struggle within his ruling party helped lead to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion of the island in 1983. The prisoners claim they were convicted in a U.S.-backed show trial to justify the invasion and eliminate the remaining inner circle of Bishop's Marxist regime. Of the 16 men and one woman, 14 are condemned to hang for murder. Three soldiers charged with the actual shooting face decades in prison for manslaughter. However, the prisoners are asking the Court of Appeal, <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>'s highest court, to throw out their December 1986 convictions for the killing of <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> and several supporters Their appeal has been dragging on since May 1988, straining the tiny island's treasury and the patience of many of the nation's 90,000 residents, who have little sympathy for the prisoners `` The people are fed up with it,'' said <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON>, editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Grenadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION>, an independent weekly newspaper. `` It's been going on and on and on. ... They want it finished with.'' The original High Court trial lasted nearly eight months, and it took a year to produce a 9,000-page court record. The 13 defense lawyers won a six-month delay to prepare the appeal. Seven months into the appeal, the president of the three-judge court died, and the appeal had to start again with a new president. At the current pace, it will go on through fall because the six-lawyer prosecution team has n't even started its case. Meanwhile, the Grenadian government is paying court costs as well as the fees and expenses of the 10 Jamaican lawyers representing those prisoners who claimed indigency. So far, the case has cost the government $ 2.7 million, or 5 percent of the nation's annual $ 55 million budget. `` It's bleeding us, but we're prepared to spend that sort of money ... so that we can say, ` Look at the sacrifice we're prepared to make,''' to give the defendants a fair trial, said Justice Minister <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>. The killing of <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON>, a popular prime minister, resulted from a dispute over leadership of his radical People's Revolutionary Government. A hard-line <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, led by <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Coard </PERSON>, took control and placed the prime minister under house arrest. On Oct. 19, 1983, hundreds of Bishop supporters converged on his residence and set him free. However, troop reinforcements rushed in, allegedly on orders of the military council. <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON>, three members of his Cabinet _ including his pregnant mistress, Education Minister <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleft </PERSON> _ and four other people were lined up against a wall and shot by three soldiers. A witness said one assailant slit <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON>'s throat long after he was clearly dead and also cut off a finger to steal a ring. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> ordered the invasion involving 1,900 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops and small forces from other <LOCATION> Carribean </LOCATION> island nations. He said he wanted to protect the lives of about 1,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens in <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> and help restore democracy. Those on death row include <PERSON> Coard </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>'s former deputy prime minister; his wife, <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON>; the former armed forces commander, Gen. <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>; and the former ambassador to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Cornwall </PERSON>. The prisoners have accused authorities of human rights abuses ranging from withholding of sheets, blankets and underwear to beatings, bread-and-water diets and long periods of solitary confinement. Mrs. <PERSON> Coard </PERSON>, a former member of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> who wrote a book in prison called `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> War on One Woman,'' claims she has been held in solitary confinement for the past 4 -LCB- years and allowed to see her husband only in court. Prime Minister <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaize </PERSON> scoffed at the prisoners' allegations, and <PERSON> Terrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Marryshow </PERSON>, leader of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Maurice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, called them `` only the victims of a situation that they themselves created.
</TEXT>
