<FIRST>r p PM-LogElection     06-26 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Log Election,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oregonians Vote On Keeping Logs Home To Save Jobs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> voters face a measure Tuesday that urges <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to let the state halt shipments of raw logs overseas when domestic lumber mills are starving for timber and workers' jobs are jeopardized. The ballot proposal, called Measure 2, seeks to ban export of logs cut on state land and calls on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to make permanent a ban of export of logs cut on federal land. Both supporters and opponents view Measure 2 as a symbolic test of the public will with jobs at mills jeopardized by both the high prices for raw logs and by environmentalist lawsuits aimed at protecting the rare Northern spotted owl and the ancient forests where they live. `` This is the first opportunity anybody in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has had to say ` We want timber jobs, we need timber jobs.' That's really the issue on Tuesday,'' said <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Stout </PERSON>, vice president for lands and timber for <ORGANIZATION> Bohemia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a lumber company in <LOCATION> Eugene </LOCATION> that has contributed $ 100,000 in support of Measure 2. But because of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling on the same issue five years ago, the options of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> voters are strictly limited. The high court ruled that only <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has the right to restrict trade, declaring an <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> law banning log exports unconstitutional. Because of the ruling, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would have to pass enabling legislation for the state export ban to become effective, even if it is passed Tuesday as most expect it will. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is seeking just the opposite, having proposed to lift a ban of exports of logs cut on federal land, currently in effect on a year-to-year basis, to take advantage of premium prices paid by log buyers in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Within the timber industry itself, opinions are mixed. Many companies make money exporting unprocessed logs, while others are struggling obtain logs for their mills. The <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes export restrictions, has decided to concentrate its efforts on defeating the enabling legislation in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, rather than seeking victory in Tuesday's referendum, said association executive director <PERSON> Rolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Glerum </PERSON>. `` We did n't feel we could raise the money to fight'' Measure 2, said <PERSON> Glerum </PERSON>. `` Even if we were to win it, it still would n't have any effect. The whole thing is triggered by the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' The group's members include <ORGANIZATION> Weyerhaeuser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the leading exporter of raw logs in the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, as well as stevedoring companies, shippers and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Longshoremen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warehousemen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. `` One reason we oppose this is we feel it is the camel's nose under the tent,'' said <PERSON> Glerum </PERSON>, because supporters `` would just as soon see all log exports banned.'' Indeed, a recent White Paper from the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> pointed to stopping all log exports as a quick fix to the timber supply crunch that has plagued <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> mills the past year. <PERSON> Glerum </PERSON> and other opponents expect Measure 2 to pass. A recent poll by The Oregonian newspaper showed support running more than 8-to-1. A campaign spending report from May 26 showed Citizens to Save Oregon Jobs raised nearly $ 800,000 to push for passage, primarily from non-exporting timber companies. `` We're talking primarily about <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> logs for <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> jobs,'' said <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Amedeo </PERSON>, a lobbyist who serves on the steering committee for the campaign. `` The big battle, because it is a non-traditional election date, is to get enough voters to the polls. `` I think in terms of sending a message back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, which is part of what the ballot measure does, the more people who vote, the more significant the message.'' State Rep. <PERSON> Bernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Agrons </PERSON> was one of the few voices in the Legislature opposing the measure. A former vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Weyerhaeuser </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Agrons </PERSON> said the measure would deprive the common school fund and counties of revenues from state timber. Last year, $ 12.5 million in state timber revenues went to the common school fund and $ 18.3 million went to local governments, predominantly schools. Export logs are generally considered to bring a premium price about 25 percent higher than domestic logs.
