Indians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Kansas-based company faces a criminal investigation based on allegations that it stole oil from Indian-owned wells, according to a spokesman for a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> probe stems from information about <ORGANIZATION> Koch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> gathered by a special investigating committee of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Indian Affairs, spokesman <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> said. `` This has been referred to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney,'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON>, a spokesman for <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> officials and representatives of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> will meet before a formal investigation begins, although no date has been set for the meeting Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, said her office can `` neither confirm nor deny the existence of an ongoing investigation.'' The special <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee focused on <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, the country's largest independent oil purchaser, at a May 10 hearing in which witnesses said <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> employees purposely mismeasured oil from wells on Indian lands In a 57-page statement issued June 8, <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said the committee `` unjustly defamed <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> and caused severe damage to its reputation and business.'' The 49-year-old company said the figures the committee used in its allegations were inaccurate, and that comparisons with other companies were based on noncomparable statistics. The committee used `` anecdotal evidence which was misleading at best and false at worst'' at the hearing, the Koch statement said. But <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> said the committee stands by its findings. `` The committee's investigators caught <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> employees in the act of stealing oil on six separate occasions,'' he said. `` Koch gaugers and supervisors also admitted to committee investigators that it was company policy to mismeasure oil.'' <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> said documents the committee subpoenaed from <LOCATION> Koch </LOCATION> and almost 30 other companies corroborated the committee's findings. He said the committee will review <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>'s June 8 statement before making its final report, sometime this fall. The special committee has been investigating all areas of Indian affairs and came upon the <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> case while probing federal agencies assigned to protecting Indian lands.
