<HEAD>Lobbyists Vying to Represent Zaire President in US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Mobotu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sese </PERSON> <PERSON> Seko </PERSON>'s poor human rights record is n't deterring <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lobbyists from scrambling to represent the wealthy leader, who visits <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this week. `` People see <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> as the gold at the end of the rainbow,'' said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Kloberg </PERSON>, whose lobbying and public relations firm recently signed a two-year contract to lobby for <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> government interests at $ 300,000. The effort to win <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON>'s approval provides a glimpse into the often-murky world of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lobbyists, where high-priced public relations consultants compete to put the best face on foreign leaders and businesses. <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> has reputedly amassed a large personal fortune during the 24 years he has ruled <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>. He is an appealing target for entrepreneurs claiming they can open doors for him in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and get him favorable media coverage despite <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>'s poor human rights record and allegations of widespread corruption. `` People promise <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> they can change things here for him, open doors, and then they ca n't deliver,'' said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Kloberg </PERSON>, who represents several Third World countries with unpopular reputations in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. His company has been seeking to bolster congressional support in advance of the <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> visit, especially in light of the shrinking budget for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The competition to represent foreign leaders sometimes leaves congressional staffers and <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials confused, such as when they were told several months ago by two rival lobbying firms that each was organizing <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON>'s visit. Their confusion was compounded when it transpired that the better known and more prestigious of the two _ the partnership of Black, <PERSON> Manafort </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Stone </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> _ had not been picked. But officials at that company say they are still negotiating to represent <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON>. Lobbyists representing foreign governments must register with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, where the files show that many contracts to represent <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> lasted only a year. It's not unusual for governments to switch lobbyists, but the turnover rate for <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> is believed to be particularly high. One company, <ORGANIZATION> Weaver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>, was paid $ 500,000 just to promote foreign investment in <LOCATION> flora </LOCATION> and fauna culture projects in <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>. Aside from the paid lobbyists, there is a network of unpaid officials, many of them businessmen, who know <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> and take on tasks for him. One example is <PERSON> Mamadi </PERSON> <PERSON> Diane </PERSON>, whose company has a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government contract to ship food aid to several African countries. <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> helped set up a recent visit to <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> by 17 black mayors of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities. The trip, paid for by <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>'s government, may have done more damage than good. It incurred the wrath of many black mayors opposed to <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON>'s repressive tactics and his ties with the white government of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.
