<HEAD>USDA, States Help Promote Organic Farming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Advocates of organic farming are generous in their praise, saying it is a way for crop producers to make money and save the environment at the same time. Even the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which had been rather stodgy about producing wheat, corn, soybeans, vegetables and other crops with reduced or eliminated doses of chemicals has adjusted. Numerous conferences and research efforts have marked <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s new journey into organic farming, but it was <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the 1985 farm law that really gave the department its marching orders, along with a $ 4 million appropriation later on. The department even used a new term _ Low Input Sustainable Agriculture, or LISA _ to include what had been loosely referred to as organic, sustainable or alternative methods of farming. Comparatively, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> is doing much more today in programs to help small farmers and to assist both large and small producers find alternative methods of production. By using less commercial fertilizer and pesticides, it is hoped that producers can reduce costs and thereby improve profits. But a Washington-based, non-profit advocacy group, the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> in the Public Interest, says organic and low-chemical farming `` is flourising at the state level'' while the federal effort is moving slowly. A new study by the center found that half the states have `` significant activities to promote sustainable agriculture,'' including strong efforts in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. `` Here in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, proponents have to scratch and claw just to hang on to a tiny $ 4.45 million sustainable agriculture program that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration and the chemical lobby want to kill,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>, author of the center's report. `` In contrast,'' he said, `` states are spending more money on a greater variety of ambitious programs to increase the production and marketing of foods grown with few or no synthetic pesticides and fertilizers.'' Other studies by advocates of low-input agriculture support claims that crop yields often are comparable to those from chemically treated land after a practice has been established and crop rotation carried out. But <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` If it were as simple as reducing purchased inputs and reaping the rewards, it would have been in practice years ago.'' Farmers are willing to adopt proven methods that result from the low-input concept, he recently told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> agriculture subcommittee. But the technology must be based on more than a whim and a promise. `` Farmers can not afford to take big risks with a new and unproven technology,'' <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> said. `` As we see it, LISA programs represent a long-term goal for agriculture.'' <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> said some aspects of <ORGANIZATION> LISA </ORGANIZATION> have shown good results, such as `` integrated pest management'' to reduce the amount of pesticides on crops by being more selective and careful about timing during the season. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, he said, pest management reduced the amount of pesticide used on apples by 38 percent and on onions by 31 percent. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> farmers were able to reduce pesticide use on carrots by 66 percent and on cabbage by 44 percent. At present, <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> said, low-input farming `` is still more a philosophy and spirit of farming than an easily defined set of principles.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has some summer advice about dogs and cats. `` That old bromide about hot weather discomfort tells us that horses sweat and men perspire, and ladies gently glow,'' says the department's <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` If you're a pet owner, however, you should know that dogs and cats do none of the above. Instead, they pant. And agency experts say that can lead to deadly consequences if left unchecked. `` Each year, hundreds of pets die of heat, usually because their owners just are n't aware of how quickly heat can kill,'' said veterinarian <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwindaman </PERSON>, who heads the agency's animal care staff. `` If you leash your dog outside, make certain it can move easily to a shady spot. Make plenty of water available to it as well, especially if you'll be away from home for long periods.'' Pets should never be left unattended in a vehicle, he said. And cracking a window an inch or two will not adequately protect an animal. Heat in a car can rise to 160 degrees in a very short time. As for car trips, <PERSON> Schwindaman </PERSON> said that for a highly nervous animal even a brief ride can be a severe strain in hot weather. `` This is especially true if your pet is an indoor cat or dog who would be frightened simply by the surroundings and noise of an unfamiliar environment,'' he said. `` In this case, if the trip is absolutely necessary, the pet owner should make every effort to transport the animal in an air-conditioned vehicle.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report shows that catfish production continues to rise unabated, with May production up 42 percent from a year earlier to 28.9 million pounds. Through the first five months of 1989, production was 141.2 million pounds, a 15 percent increase from the same period of last year, the report said. Despite the larger output, catfish farmers are getting more for their product, averaging 76 cents per pound in May, up a penny from a year ago.
