<TEXT>
 Zoning officials did n't object to the golden pyramid or the shark-filled moat. But they had enough when <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Onan </PERSON> put a 45-foot statue of a pharoah on his front lawn. The town took him to court under a zoning ordinance that puts a 25-foot limit on structures in residential neighborhoods. The 52-year-old Onan, a construction contractor, decided on a way of getting around the regulation: He's burying the 200-ton statue of <ORGANIZATION> Ramses </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> II </ORGANIZATION> in gravel up to its knees. <PERSON> Onan </PERSON> says he intends to spend $ 25,000 to bury all but 25 feet of Ramses II. `` I love it because they're making a fool of themselves,'' <PERSON> Onan </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his pyramid home Friday. The choice of Ramses II is fitting: He ruled <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> from 1290 to 1224 B.C., and was known for his ambitious building projects _ much like <PERSON> Onan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Onan </PERSON> completed his 5-story-tall, gold-plated pyramid five years ago near <LOCATION> Wadsworth </LOCATION>, a town just south of the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> border. Townspeople have n't exactly rallied to <PERSON> Onan </PERSON>'s defense in the statue case. `` I do n't think there's anyone who had anything good to say about it,'' said Village President <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomkowiak </PERSON>.
