<HEAD>Survivor of Auschwitz Slain Over Swastika</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> survivor was beaten and stabbed to death after confronting a man he had accused of scrawling a swastika on his door, police said. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Kowalski </PERSON>, 72, was found dead Saturday in the second-floor apartment of <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> <PERSON> Zucarino </PERSON>, 36, who was charged with second-degree murder, said police spokesman Sgt. <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>. An arraignment was scheduled for today. A popular man known as `` the mayor of <LOCATION> Brighton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Kowalski </PERSON> spent his days in a rented room at the <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> boarding house tinkering with old televisions and radios and talking with friends about his native <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. `` This is n't the way God wanted it,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Solsky </PERSON>, a 72-year-old neighbor. `` He was a friend in a Jewish neighborhood who should never have died with a swastika or violently.'' <PERSON> Kowalski </PERSON>, a Jew whose family perished at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>, came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1949 and worked as a carpenter. He survived the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death camp and his wife also is a Holocaust survivor. `` She figures that he survived everything else, and then for this to happen,'' said <PERSON> Kowalski </PERSON>'s 38-year-old son, <PERSON> Lenny </PERSON>. `` The guy might have stabbed him, but the war still killed him,'' the son said. `` It was the insignia that did it. If it had n't been there, this never would have happened.'' The younger <PERSON> Kowalski </PERSON> said he was visiting with his father Saturday morning in the workshop when he noticed the swastika and a skull and crossbones scrawled in blue felt-tip pen on the door. His father quietly washed the marks from the door, the younger <PERSON> Kowalski </PERSON> said. The son complained to the landlady, <PERSON> Tuey </PERSON> <PERSON> Chin </PERSON>, who said that when she asked <PERSON> Zucarino </PERSON> about the graffiti he was holding a marker of the same blue color in his hands. But he told her he knew nothing about the drawings. A short time later, the elder <PERSON> Kowalski </PERSON> went to <PERSON> Zucarino </PERSON>'s apartment, where he confronted him about the swastika and grabbed him by the throat, police said A fight ensued. Zucarino stabbed <PERSON> Kowalski </PERSON> repeatedly with a scissors and a fork and smashed a religious statue over his head, killing him, police said. Ms. <PERSON> Chin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Zucarino </PERSON> may have attacked <PERSON> Kowalski </PERSON> with a 5-inch-high metal Statue of Liberty. She said he showed her the statue after the attack. `` I'm not sure if he hit <PERSON> Max </PERSON> over the head later with the Statue of Liberty or a religious statue,'' she said. `` But there was a Statue of Liberty all right. Brass, bronze, whatever.''
