<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Advocates for AIDS patients hailed a proposal by the chief of federal AIDS research to allow for greater distribution of experimental drugs. Dr. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allergy </ORGANIZATION> and Infectious Diseases, recommended the development of `` parallel track'' testing under which patients would have access to promising drugs as soon as they are proved safe, even while tests for effectiveness were under way. `` It's a great step forward,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Mathilde </PERSON> <PERSON> Krim </PERSON>, a founder of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for AIDS Research. `` It represents a new consensus on how to handle drug development for AIDS and life-threatening diseases in general.'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON>, co-director of Project Inform, a group of AIDS activists, said he planned to ask a committee of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> today to endorse <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON>'s idea. In a speech Friday, <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON> called for the `` compassionate distribution'' of trial drugs to ineligible applicants. `` It's clear to me that we can not just rely on the traditional approach of clinical trials,'' <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON> said during a talk at the HIV Treatment Awareness Week conference. HIV stands for human immunodeficiency virus, which causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Clinical trials are designed to test the effectiveness of drugs that have been proved non-toxic. Test subjects must meet strict requirements that typically exclude many applicants. `` We've got to rethink the rigidity with which we exclude people,'' he said. <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON> said drug companies, the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, and AIDS patients must consider the possibility of parallel track testing. `` It's not something that any one person or organization has the ability to make happen because you're involving the public and private factions,'' he said. `` The critical thing is this ca n't happen by fiat It's a concept.'' <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON>, a staunch advocate of clinical trials as the only means to discover definitive scientific answers, emphasized the continued need for rigorous studies. Part of the need for parallel tracking stems from the limited availability of drugs to treat AIDS, <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON> said. Similarly, the drug trial process is slow and limited and leaves out many patients who are eager to try experimental drugs.
