<HEAD>Conjoined Twins Celebrate Fifth Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The mother of Siamese twins who just celebrated their fifth birthday says there is no tragedy in her two girls being joined together. <PERSON> Marlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Cady </PERSON> wrote in this week's People magazine that when a stranger walks up to <PERSON> Verena </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ruthie </PERSON> and laments the youngsters' fate, `` I always tell those people that the only tragedy is in their interpretation of the girls' situation, because obviously <PERSON> Ruthie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Verena </PERSON> are happy kids. The girls, born April 13, 1984, are joined from the collarbone to the waist and share a heart, liver and parts of the intestines. Sharing a heart makes the girls tire easily and they are more susceptible to infection than most children. Mrs. <PERSON> Cady </PERSON>, whose family lives near <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, said that when the girls had pneumonia at age 9 months, she and her husband, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON>, found themselves talking about their lives as `` now or after the girls die.'' `` But when we celebrated their first birthday, we realized that we could wait for things to change until we were 105 years old, but then we would have spent the time waiting instead of living,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Cady </PERSON> wrote. She said the children have distinct personalities _ <PERSON> Ruthie </PERSON> is stubborn while <PERSON> Verena </PERSON> likes to make sure she's doing the right thing. The girls have mastered feats that doctors thought impossible. When they perfected riding a special tricycle, `` they rode up and down the street for three days, knocking on doors and ringing bells to make sure everyone knew about their new treasure.'' The twins' older sister, <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>, had been upset at all the attention the twins got but then realized they are special, their mother said. `` Sometimes I feel sorry for my sisters being attached because they do n't always want to do the same thing. But when they are n't arguing, I think they're very lucky to be together,'' <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> said Conjoined twins occur about once in 100,000 births. About half die within 48 hours of birth. Mrs. <PERSON> Cady </PERSON> said that when she thinks `` about how long they might live, it's in terms of a couple of years. We live for the present.''
