<HEAD>NRC Spurned by Three Seabrook Officials on Shutdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal inspectors told three <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> nuclear plant officials to shut down the reactor before the directive was obeyed, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> <PERSON> Dudley </PERSON>, senior <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> inspector at the plant, denied that agency officials had to grab anyone to get a response, as alleged by a <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> critic. Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., said Friday <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lando </PERSON> <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> and other commission officials told him an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> inspector grabbed a plant operator before Thursday's unplanned shutdown The <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> reported details of the shutdown based on interviews with <PERSON> Dudley </PERSON>, plant officials and others. The shutdown, on the 10th day of low-power tests at the $ 6 billion plant, prompted the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> to suspend further tests pending a review. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said he will ask an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> appeal board to stop the tests until safety issues for full-power operation are reviewed. `` The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> pointed to those same problems a year ago after a mock evacuation exercise,'' <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said. Plant spokesmen said neither the plant nor the public was endangered. But <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said the results could have been much worse at higher power. `` It's very frightening to think what would have happened if this plant had been operating at 70 to 80 percent of full power and there had been no <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> people in the control room,'' he said. Thursday's events, plant officials say, began when a malfunctioning valve on the non-nuclear side of the operation produced changes in readouts from a part called a pressurizer on the nuclear side. The change was sufficient to warrant a shutdown, spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said Sunday. One <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> inspector and then <PERSON> Dudley </PERSON> approached three plant officials pointing out the problem, but got no immediate results, the <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> said. Minutes later, an operator did shut down the plant. `` They were making a conscious decision to attempt to regain pressure control'' even though plant procedures called for a shutdown, <PERSON> Dudley </PERSON> said. An unidentified <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> inspector first approached <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>'s startup manager about the pressure reading, the <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> said. When the manager did not respond, the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> inspector approached the test director, who was closer to the scene in the control room, and the director agreed the plant should be shut, the paper said. But according to the newspaper, the test director then talked to the shift supervisor, a higher-ranking official, who said that pressure problem was being corrected on its own and there was no need to turn off the plant. <PERSON> Dudley </PERSON> stepped in at that point, approaching a still higher <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> official, the assistant operators manager, said <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Horwitz </PERSON>. The assistant manager consulted the operations manager, who acknowledged the information and deferred to the decision of the shift supervisor to continue to operate, <PERSON> Horwitz </PERSON> said.
