<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Potential jurors in the federal trial of billionaire <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>'s tax evasion case must reveal their income, what they think about rich people and whether they believe the hotel queen is an ogre. Jury selection was to begin today in the trial of the 69-year-old Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> and two former aides. She and her husband, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>, are accused of evading federal taxes by billing personal luxuries, including a marble dance floor for their mansion, as business expenses. Her 80-year-old husband has been found incompetent to stand trial because of loss of memory. The <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION> head a $ 5 billion real estate and hotel empire, mostly in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> area. In April 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION> were indicted on charges they evaded personal income taxes by disguising about $ 4 million in renovations to their <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, mansion as a business expense. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> is portrayed in advertisements as the `` Queen of the Helmsley Hotels.'' The ad campaign calls <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> <PERSON> Palace </PERSON> `` the only palace in the world where the queen stands guard.'' <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON>, lawyer for <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Turco </PERSON>, planned to hand potential jurors a questionnaire asking their incomes and attitude toward the wealthy. He said he wants to know if the potential jurors are `` biased against rich people ... or whether they've seen Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>'s ads in the newspapers and they think she's an ogre.'' <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Licari </PERSON> are charged with helping create bogus invoices to make it appear that the costly renovations on the $ 8 million, 28-room mansion were tax-deductible improvements on business properties. Among the renovations listed in the 47-count indictment were a marble dance floor installed above a swimming pool; a breakfast room; an indoor-outdoor stereo system; more than $ 370,000 in landscaping; and an assortment of furniture and paintings. The indictment said a $ 45,000 silver clock in the shape of the Helmsley Building _ a gift for <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> _ was billed to and paid by the Park Lane Hotel. Four jade art objects worth half a million dollars were paid for by four hotels as furniture purchases, the indictment said. Last fall, the <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION>' lawyer, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Feffer </PERSON>, said the false invoices were a device used by <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> and <PERSON> Licari </PERSON> `` to enable them to steal blindly from the <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION>. That's crucial to our defense.'' The case was going to court after a lengthy pretrial period during which defense lawyers filed many motions to overturn the indictment or to remove one or both of the Helmsleys from the case. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in April rejected a motion to dismiss the indictment. The motion said prosecutors engaged in misconduct because of grand jury leaks to the news media. Earlier this month, a federal judge found <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> unable to assist in his defense because of memory lapses and reasoning difficulties. The ruling did not dismiss the charges against <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> but indefinitely delayed his trial. The judge noted that doctors believed <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>'s mental deterioration, cause by several mild strokes, would continue and that it was unlikely he would be tried.
