<HEAD>`Making a Living, Not a Killing' _ PC-Write's Bob Wallace</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to RESTORE full name of software; PICKS UP
3rd graf pvs, ``I encourage ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's an unwritten law of American business: You ca n't sell computer software on the honor system and expect to be a success. Unless you're <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, president, owner and ex-chief programmer of Seattle-based Quicksoft, publisher of PC-Write, the acclaimed `` shareware'' word-processor for personal computers. Then you break the unwritten law. `` I encourage people to copy the software and then encourage them to pay for it after using it. It's like public television,'' the 40-year-old <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> said last week. Users who pay and register get extra benefits: the printed manual, telephone support, <PERSON> Quicksoft </PERSON>'s newsletter and updates of the program. `` But then there are intangible benefits: You're doing the right thing, you're helping us out, keeping us in business,'' he said. And that leads to newer and better versions of PC-Write. `` I do n't worry about the people who do n't register. I worry about the people who do register,'' he said. `` I want to make sure they're happy. ... `` If they're happy and we're making a reasonable profit, that's good. It's good enough for Quicksoft, with about 30 employees, to expand its product base, too. On Tuesday, the company announced its new file-search and `` hypertext'' information-linking utility scheduled for late-summer shipping. <PERSON> Quicksoft </PERSON> also has published its first catalog of third-party software it selects and supports for use with PC-Write. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, whose catch-phrase is `` making a living, not a killing,'' chose his profession at age 11. `` I read a Reader's Digest article, ` The Man Who Talked to Machines,''' he said `` I was one of the people that just knew, then, I would be a programmer.'' He found computers to work on with an Explorer Scout troop sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, then at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION>. `` I got kind of discouraged because computers were so expensive. I could n't own one and I really wanted to own one, so I kind of got distracted and went off. I was living on an island in Puget Sound for a while,'' he said. The first personal computers appeared about the time he founded the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in 1976. He went to work for The Retail Computer Store in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. In 1978, he was the 10th employee hired by <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the software company that created the IBM-standard personal computer operating systems. `` Sometime in'82, I found myself thinking, ` Gee, <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> is getting huge and I'm kind of getting lost here,''' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> had 300 employees then; it now has about 3,800 worldwide. He started writing a program for word processing. `` I thought I could do something people would really like and really felt right, but I did n't know if I could explain that. I could n't really run an ad saying, ` Buy my word processor: It feels good.'' He could, however, share his word processor using the electronic bulletin boards of computer hobbyists. That eliminated distribution and advertising expenses. The first version, 1.0, was introduced in August 1983, with 150 copies sent to the press and 150 to bulletin boards. A PC Magazine reviewer suggested changes. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> made them. By February 1984, <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> had written version 1.3 and the reviewer liked it. `` That review pretty much started us out. It generated enough interest and revenue so that I could hire our first employee, uh, who I later married.'' <PERSON> Megan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, an artist, draws <PERSON> Quicksoft </PERSON>'s trademark `` office cat'' on the company's literature. PC-Write typically is rated as good as or better than other full-featured word processors costing five times more than its $ 89 registration fee. It's anybody's guess how many copies of PC-Write are out there. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> says the best estimates come from magazine surveys, which typically estimate that 6 percent of their readers use PC-Write. `` I discount that down to maybe 4 percent, and that's somewhere between half a million and 1 million users. And that's real exciting,'' he said. `` Working from the other end, we know we have paid users of about 125,000, of which 45,000 are full, registered users and the other 80,000 are on group licenses _ corporations and universities,'' he said. He expects revenues this year to be between $ 2 million and $ 3 million. Sales declined to $ 1.7 million last year from $ 2 million in 1987. He blames the slump on himself, for putting off the decision to step down as chief programmer to take up exclusively the presidency of <LOCATION> Quicksoft </LOCATION>. A final thought from <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>: `` Our business is based on people being honest and people are. That's why we're successful.''
