<HEAD>Dissident Leader Goes on Trial, Supporters Battle Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A leading dissident accused of making an illegal trip to Communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> went on trial today, and supporters chanted anti-government slogans and battled with police. About 500 radical students brandishing metal pipes, clubs and rocks hurled hundreds of firebombs at riot police as the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan went on trial for making a trip to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to discuss unifying the nations. `` Release unification fighter Moon Ik-hwan!'' students yelled, `` Down with -LRB- President -RRB- <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo!'' Several hundred police with shields defended themselves by swinging captured metal pipes. Some students and police were injured, but numbers were unavailable on arrests or injuries. Students from at least four colleges took part in the clash, which occurred on a city street in front of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sogang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. About 1,500 police guarded the courthouse where <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>'s trial opened. Police arrested 13 radical students, chanting anti-government slogans, who seized the rooftop of a nearby six-story building and erected a large banner saying `` immediately release patriotic unification fighter Moon.'' <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> was brought to the courthouse in prison garb under heavy security. His hands were tied with rope, but he smiled and waved at supporters. The trial opening was delayed when about 200 Moon supporters mounted a sit-in outside the courtroom demanding they be allowed to use courtroom seats occupied by 50 police officers. No arrests were reported. The judge asked some officers to leave so that more <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> supporters could be seated. Moon is charged with violation of the National Security Law for his nine-day trip to the north in March. He talked to North Korean leader <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> about national unification, a popular issue with student protesters in the capitalist south. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s anti-communist government forbids unsanctioned trips to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, its bitter enemy, and maintains that dialogue on unification must be carried out through government channels. If convicted, <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> could face the death penalty, although that is not considered likely. Also today, arrest warrants were issued for three radical students the government says have encouraged people to participate in the World Youth Festival, which is to be held in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> July 1-8. The government has banned participation. The students have been charged with violation of national security laws, prosecutors said. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>, 71, and his traveling companion <PERSON> Yoo </PERSON> <PERSON> Won-ho </PERSON>, a 59-year-old businessman, were arrested April 13 when they returned to <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> after stops in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. They have been in jail since then. Defense lawyers argued that the prosecution should drop charges against <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yoo </PERSON> on grounds the indictment is unconstitutional. Repeating his earlier statements, <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> told the court that he visited the north to seek reunification. The Korean peninsula was divided after World War II. In 1950, the north invaded the south and started the three-year Korean War.
