<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A legislator today suggested the nation withdraw its highest military order from former <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, who was given the honor 33 years after the end of World War II, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, who rose to major general serving as a political officer in the war, was given the jewel-encrusted Order of Victory in 1978, the official agency said. He died in 1982. Supreme Soviet deputy <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Likhachev </PERSON> said many people see the decoration as one of <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>'s undeserved rewards. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> noted, however, that the legislature has no power to revoke the award. Such a move would further discredit <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, who now is condemned widely for plunging the economy into a crisis and stagnating the rest of Soviet society. His name has been stripped off cities and ships, and his relatives have lost some benefits given to family members of a Soviet leader. The Supreme Soviet, the nation's first full-time lawmaking body, convened today to confirm <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> members and organize writing bills and ratifying treaties, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. These are new powers for the legislature, a division of the larger <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies that began work May 25. In closed hearings last week, legislative committees rejected at least four of more than 60 nominees to ministerial and other senior posts. The fight now moves to the full 542-member body. One chamber, the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalities </ORGANIZATION>, decided today that committees in both houses should consider bills before publication in the press, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. Several deputies objected to the large number of military and defense industry representatives on a committee to oversee defense and the dreaded <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> secret police. But they were told experts were assigned deliberately to committees in their area of professional expertise, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>, the government daily, reported today that the committee's hearings will be behind closed doors despite calls for more openness in those areas. The chamber approved the composition of its committees after changes, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said without elaborating. The legislature also is to consider bills on raising pensions and the rights of deputies, and to set priorities for tackling the nation's economic and social problems, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The Soviet of Nationalities elected Ukrainian poet <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Oleinik </PERSON>, a reformer from <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, as one of its deputy chairmen, and the Soviet of Unions elected Moldavian <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Mokanu </PERSON> to a similar job. Monday's separate sessions of the two chambers, originally to be televised nationally, did not appear on the air or in the broadcast schedule. A spokeswoman at the state <PERSON> Gostelradio </PERSON> said officials decided there was no need to televise the session.
