<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Miranda     06-26 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Miranda,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Police Can Stray From Warning Language</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today gave police permission to stray from the precise wording of the famous Miranda warnings given to criminal suspects. The decision, reached by a 5-4 vote, reinstated an <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> man's conviction and 35-year prison sentence for attempted murder The warning, familiar to every fan of television police shows, was created by the high court in a 1966 decision called Miranda vs. <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. It was designed to bolster criminal suspects' Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination. Under the court ruling, police must warn suspects in custody of their right to remain silent, that anything they say can be used against them and that they have a right to a lawyer's help before answering any questions. Suspects also must be told that a lawyer will be provided to them if they can not afford to hire one and that the warnings must be given before any police interrogation begins. In the case decided today, <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, police questioned <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON> in 1982 about an attempted murder after reading him a warning that included this paragraph: `` You have a right to the advice and presence of a lawyer even if you can not afford one. We have no way of giving you a lawyer but one will be appointed for you, if you wish, if and when you go to court.'' <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON> subsequently confessed to the crime, and did so again 29 hours later after being read a Miranda warning that did not include the `` if and when'' language. Like some other states, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> does not provide pennyless criminal suspects with free lawyers until their first appearance in court. The Miranda right to a lawyer's help is accommodated by police not initiating any contact with a suspect who has asked for legal help. The 7th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled in <LOCATION> Eagan </LOCATION>'s case that the `` if and when'' language of the warning <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> police gave him was confusing. The wording could lead someone to think he properly may be questioned by police without a lawyer, the appeals court said. Other federal appeals courts have allowed warnings containing such wording. Today, the justices said the 7th Circuit court was wrong. `` In our view, the court of appeals misapprehended the effect of the inclusion of the ` if and when you go to court' language in Miranda warnings,'' Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> wrote. `` This instruction accurately described the procedure for the appointment of counsel in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>,'' he said. The court also ruled that the 1966 <PERSON> Miranda </PERSON> decision does not require that lawyers be provided as soon as they are requested _ only that police halt their questioning. Justices <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> joined <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> in the majority. Justices <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> dissented. In a 1981 decision, the court said `` talismanic incantations'' of a defendant's rights are not required so long as the right to a lawyer's help is not linked to `` a future point in time after the police interrogation.'' Both <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> prosecutors and <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON> cited the 1981 ruling as favorable to their side. <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON> telephoned <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> police on May 16, 1982 and told them he had found a dead, naked woman along the <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> shore in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. When he led police to her, the still-alive woman looked at <LOCATION> Eagan </LOCATION> and exclaimed, `` Why did you stab me?'' The woman later testified that <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON> and two other men had taken her to the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> beach from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and that she had sex with the two other men. When she refused <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON>, she said, he stabbed her. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> police turned the case over to <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> police. The case is <PERSON> Duckworth </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON>, 88-317.
</TEXT>
