 The Afghan government will free rebel prisoners in exchange for Soviet soldiers captured by guerrillas during the 10-year-old war, rebel sources said today. Soviet diplomats, however, said final approval of the prisoner swap must come from the Soviet-backed government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. An exchange agreement was reached at a fourth round of talks today between Moslem guerrilla representatives and the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>, a guerrilla spokesman said on condition of anonymity. He said both sides will exchange lists of prisoners at talks to be held within the next week. He said the Soviets endorsed the principle of exchanging prisoners at one time, en masse, as previously demanded by the insurgents. A Soviet Embassy statement, however, said <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> will open talks with <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> on the proposed exchange. `` If the Russians agreed then <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> will also,'' the guerrilla spokesman said. The guerrillas claim 40,000 of their people are missing in action. They say they are holding between 50 and 75 Soviet soldiers inside <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> says 311 of its troops have gone missing since its sent troops to bolster the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government's fight against the anti-communist guerrillas nine years ago. The last Red Army troops withdrew in February under a U.N.-brokered agreement. This latest round of prisoner negotiations comes while an eight-member <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> delegation is visiting <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, including three mothers and a father of <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> soldiers missing in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. They insist their group is unofficial. Delegation spokesman <PERSON> Iona </PERSON> <PERSON> Andronov </PERSON> said that over the past two days, `` We s