<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Appeal in Yonkers Desegregation Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected arguments by citizen groups in <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, that a federal judge illegally ordered construction of 1,000 low-cost homes to help desegregate the city. The justices, without comment, threw out an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> Save </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yonkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and others. It contended that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON>. Sand exceeded his authority in ordering the desegregation plan. The <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> case attracted national attention a year ago when four <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> councilmen refused to obey Sand's orders to adopt the plan and were fined $ 3,500 each for contempt of court. Faced with massive layoffs of city workers, the city council reversed itself on Sept. 10, 1988, by voting to comply with the judge's order to build the low-cost homes. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last March agreed to decide whether Sand had the power to fine the councilmen. A ruling in that case is expected sometime in 1990. But the high court previously left intact Sand's 1985 ruling that <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> officials intentionally and unlawfully promoted racial segregation through their housing and school policies. The suit against the officials was begun by the federal government in the waning days of President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s administration in 1980 In the case acted on today, the citizens groups said Sand's order to build the homes in middle-class areas would leave untouched racial segregation in the city's predominantly black Hispanic area. The case is Save <ORGANIZATION> Yonkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> vs. Sand, 88-1767.
