<HEAD>Court Eases Use of Racketeering Law in Civil Suits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, broadly interpreting a key federal anti-racketeering law, made it easier today to use the law in civil lawsuits against businesses accused of fraud. The court said unanimously that the law applies to more than what is traditionally described as organized crime. Also, Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said for the court that to prove a pattern of racketeering activity under the law, a private plaintiff or a prosecutor must show at least two criminal acts `` within a single scheme that were related and that amounted to, or threatened the likelihood of, continued criminal activity.'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> rejected arguments that a plaintiff or prosecutor must prove `` separate illegal schemes'' to demonstrate a pattern of racketeering activity. Moreover, he continued, the law is designed to apply to more than traditional organized crime. `` The occasion for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' action was the perceived need to combat organized crime,'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said. `` But <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for cogent reasons chose to enact a more general statute, one which, although it had organized crime as its focus, was not limited in application to organized crime.'' The court unanimously reinstated a lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> by <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> consumers. The suit was based on alleged violations of the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act, or RICO. The 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> dismissed the suit, which accused Northwestern Bell of bribing state public utility officials. The consumers say the phone company in 1980 began trying illegally to win rate increases by offering gifts, employment and other favors to members of the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The appeals court ruled that the phone company's customers failed to prove `` a pattern of racketeering activity'' required to make a case under RICO. The 8th Circuit court said a single fraudulent scheme is insufficient, ruling that at least two schemes must be alleged. Other federal appeals courts have allowed civil RICO suits based on numerous acts advancing only one fraudulent scheme. It is not unusual nowadays to find at least one RICO claim in lawsuits involving virtually any business dispute. The stigma attached to being linked in public court documents to alleged racketeering can be powerful leverage for out-of-court settlements. Winners of RICO lawsuits may collect triple damages and lawyer fees, both of which generally are not available under state anti-fraud laws. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers, in a friend-of-the-court brief submitted last year, sided with the phone customers in urging the justices to interpret the RICO law broadly and reinstate the lawsuit. Also backing the customers were 14 states _ <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. Other interests urged the high court to bar the lawsuit. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> said in a friend-of-the-court brief that `` private civil RICO actions have become a tool of harassment ... against legitimate businesses and labor organizations.'' During an oral argument session before the justices last November, a lawyer for <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> said the 1970 law is aimed at thwarting organized crime, and should not be used against otherwise legitimate businesses accused of fraud. But the lawyer representing the company's customers said businesses that engage in fraudulent acts `` forfeit the right to call themselves legitimate.'' The case is H.J. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1252.
