<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeals Saying Italian-Americans Unlawfully Barred
as Jurors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected appeals by three convicted drug dealers who said Italian-Americans unlawfully were barred from serving as jurors at their trial. The court, without comment, left intact the case of the three men convicted in connection with the shipment of cocaine from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. The three are <PERSON> Giacomo </PERSON> <PERSON> DiNorscio </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, each sentenced to 30 years in prison, and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Truglia </PERSON>, sentenced to 10 years. At their 1986 trial in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, federal prosecutors used what are known as peremptory _ or automatic _ challenges to exclude five potential jurors with Italian surnames. The defendants said elimination of those potential jurors violated a 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that said prosecutors never may disqualify potential jurors based on their race. The 1986 case involved exclusion of black potential jurors, and the justices said prosecutors must explain their reasons for peremptory challenges if there is evidence the exclusions are racially motivated. The 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last December ruled against the defendants in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> case. The appeals court said they failed to show that `` persons with Italian surnames ... are themselves an identifiable ethnic group that shares common backgrounds and ideas linked to a single culture and group loyalties.'' The appeals court said there was no evidence `` this group has been systematically excluded from jury service in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>.'' The 3rd Circuit court also said the defendants failed to prove any actual prejudice against them, particularly since two jurors who did serve at the trial had Italian surnames. Claims by <PERSON> DiNorscio </PERSON> and <PERSON> Truglia </PERSON> that five years was tacked on to their prison sentences improperly also were rejected by the appeals court. The five years were added under a federal law that permits longer sentences for defendants who commit crimes while free on bail awaiting trial. The defendants said they were not alerted to the possibility of the additional prison sentences when freed on bail. The appeals court also rejected <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>'s argument that he was indicted by a grand jury that lacked adequate representation by blacks, Hispanic-Americans and people with less than high school educations. The cases are <PERSON> DiNorscio </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-1664, and <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-6875.
