<HEAD>Supreme Court Will Hear Appeal in Houston Labor Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to set guidelines on when employers may withdraw recognition of a labor union after hiring new workers to break a strike. The court said it will hear a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration appeal of a ruling favoring an employer in a case stemming from a 1979 strike against a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> laboratory supplies company. <ORGANIZATION> Curtin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Matheson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> was struck in 1979 by workers at its warehouse in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> after a union contract expired and the company locked out all 27 <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union members employed there. Five of the 27 employees crossed the picket line when the strike began June 13, 1979. The company 12 days later hired 29 new employees to replace the remaining 22 strikers. When the union later offered to end the strike under terms previously offered by management, the company withdrew the offer along with its recognition of the union as the workers' bargaining agent. The National Labor Relations Board in 1987 said the company illegally withdrew its recognition of the union. The board said the company acted without adequate reason to believe the union lacked support from a majority of the workers then at the plant. The 5th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> overruled the board last November. `` The company was justified in doubting that the striker replacements supported the union,'' the appeals court said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration lawyers said the labor board properly refused to accept the company's presumption that the union had lost the support of the majority of workers. Strikebreakers may choose to work for financial reasons or they may disapprove of a strike while still supporting the union, <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers told the court. The case is <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Curtin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matheson </PERSON>, 88-1685.
