<HEAD>Orders Restudy of Dispute Over Philadelphia Transit Drug Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today ordered a lower court to restudy a dispute over drug and alcohol testing for employees of a mass transit agency in the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> area. The justices said the lower court should re-examine its ruling in light of recent decisions that allowed the <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> railroad to adopt drug tests for its workers without first bargaining with its unions and allowed mandatory drug testing of railroad employees involved in accidents. In the case acted on today, a lower court ruling was challenged by both the workers and their employer, the <ORGANIZATION> Southeastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> SEPTA </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> SEPTA </ORGANIZATION> and its workers are unhappy with different aspects of a ruling last December by the 3rd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. The appeals court said <ORGANIZATION> SEPTA </ORGANIZATION> did not violate the privacy rights of employees in `` safety sensitive'' jobs by requiring them to undergo random drug and alcohol tests. But the appeals court, based on narrower grounds, barred the agency from testing any employees covered by the federal Railway Labor Act. The federal law bars railroads from unilaterally adopting any such major change in working conditions, the appeals court said. It said the unions that challenged the tests are entitled to mediation and conciliation procedures spelled out by the law. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled on June 19 that <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> may use previously approved physical fitness tests to screen for drug use. It said the addition of drug screening is a minor change not warranting collective bargaining. <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION>'s tests are not random. They are to be administered periodically to all workers during routine physical examinations. In addition, employees returning to work after an absence would have to undergo the tests. The high court last March 21 issued two key rulings on drug and alcohol testing in the workplace. The justices upheld blood and urine tests for railroad workers involved in accidents, and upheld urine tests for <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> employees seeking drug-enforcement jobs. In the case acted on today, <ORGANIZATION> SEPTA </ORGANIZATION> announced in 1987 its plan to require random urine and breathalyzer tests for thousands of workers with jobs affecting the safety of its more than a million daily bus, train, streetcar and subway riders. The agency also adopted tests for employees returning to work after absences. Those tests were declared unconstitutional by the 3rd Circuit court, and <ORGANIZATION> SEPTA </ORGANIZATION> and its unions subsequently reached a settlement on the return-to-work tests. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> SEPTA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> VS. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1486, and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> SEPTA </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1653.
