<HEAD>Court Rules in Resident Alien Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused today to allow resident aliens sue in federal court to collect retroactive unemployment benefits from the state of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. The action comes 11 days after the justices ruled that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has the power to strip state governments of their constitutional immunity against private lawsuits. At issue in the <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> case was whether such state immunity should be overcome. Lower courts said no. A policy of the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s division of employment and training of refusing to pay unemployment benefits to some previously employed aliens lawfully living in the state sparked a 1984 lawsuit. The suit sought to have the policy declared a violation of the Federal Unemployment Tax Act and to collect benefits it alleged were wrongfully withheld. A federal trial judge ruled that the aliens would have to pursue their claims through state administrative proceedings. The aliens appealed, but the 10th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> dismissed the suit Nov. 29. Noting that state court rulings and changes in immigration law made clear that the aliens were eligible for unemployment benefits, the appeals court rendered moot the need for future relief. Regarding the claims for back benefits, the 10th Circuit court said the 11th Amendment prohibits such a raid on the state treasury in federal court. The amendment says: `` The judicial power of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should not be construed to extend to any suit ... -LRB- against a state -RRB- by citizens of another state or by citizens or subjects of any foreign state.'' In decisions dating back to 1890, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has barred anyone, in-state or out, from suing an unconsenting state _ or state officials if the real target is a state's treasury. But in recent years, the court has allowed some federal court lawsuits against states. In the case today, lawyers for the aliens said the 10th Circuit court's bar on federal suits to recover back unemployment benefits was in conflict with rulings by other federal appeals courts. The case is <PERSON> Esparza </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON>, 88-1432.
