<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-LawyerFees     06-26 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Lawyer Fees,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Illinois Doctor's Appeal in Lawyers-Fee Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected an appeal by an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> doctor ordered to pay $ 254,000 in lawyers' fees to those who successfully challenged a state abortion law. The court, consistent with a ruling by the justices last week in an airline industry bias cae, let stand a lower court ruling stemming from a 1979 lawsuit challenging an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> abortion-regulating law that included criminal penalties for physicians who violated it. A group of doctors sued various state officials, saying the law violated physicians' rights and those of their patients. A federal judge barred enforcement of the law. Soon thereafter, Dr. <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON> and two others asked to intervene in the case as defenders of the law. <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON> said he was acting to defend his patients' interests and his own professional interests. Diamond and another doctor, who has since died, appealed to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 to overrule lower court decisions and reinstate the law. State officials dropped out of the case, declining to pursue it to the nation's high court. The justices in 1986 ruled that <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> lacked legal standing to appeal, thus leaving intact the victory won by the law's challengers. A federal judge and the 7th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> subsequently ordered <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> to help reimburse the winners' legal fees. His share of the attorneys' fees, with interest, is $ 254,000. The 7th Circuit court ruled last May that Diamond can be forced to help pay the fees even though he did not violate the constitutional rights of those who challenged the law. Only public officials and their agents may commit constitutional violations. The public officials in the case were sued under a key civil rights law that authorizes reimbursement of attorneys' fees to encourage legal representation for those whose rights are violated. Diamond and the others who intervened in the case in defense of the law `` for all practical purposes'' became the `` alter ego'' of the state officials, the appeals court said. `` We can not ... ignore the fact that the intervenors' unilateral decision ... to join with the state defendants in adamantly defending the constitutionality of the abortion act rendered them full-fledged parties to the lawsuit,'' the appeals court said. It added that the intervenors `` were thoroughly beaten'' in numerous court proceedings by the law's challengers. The appeals court also rejected Diamond's arguments that forcing him to help pay the other side's legal fees chills his free-speech rights. A fee reimbursement system is not unlawful `` simply because it forces those who choose voluntarily to interject themselves into such lawsuits to think twice before engaging in battle,'' the appeals court said. The case is Diamond vs. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, 88-664.
