<FIRST>r w PM-DeadSeaScrolls     06-26 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dead Sea Scrolls,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Says Needless Delays Hurting Work on Dead Sea Scrolls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An article published today in an archaeological review said an Israeli government timetable for scholarly work on the Dead Sea Scrolls is a `` hoax and a fraud'' that will delay publication of documents that may hold new insights on early Judaism and Christianity. One member of the scroll publication team, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Divinity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, conceded that publication of the documets is proceeding slowly but said the `` fraud'' charge in the magazine <ORGANIZATION> Biblical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archaeology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> is `` certainly incorrect.'' The article by <PERSON> Hershel </PERSON> <PERSON> Shanks </PERSON>, editor of the review, said the team of scholars assigned to the task, originally by the government of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and later by the government of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, `` has now become more an obstacle to publication than a source of information.'' Shanks called for opening the materials to research by `` any scholar who so wishes.'' The article included a copy of the timetable published by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Antiquities </ORGANIZATION>, which calls for completion of the work by the end of 1996. `` It is a hoax and a fraud,'' <PERSON> Shanks </PERSON> wrote. `` It is not a timetable at all. It does n't specifiy what happens if the scholars do n't meet the timetable.'' Cross, reached by telephone in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, said, `` The notion that the timetable is a fraud, if that is the way it is put, is certainly incorrect.'' `` Timetables in scholarly work often are not kept precisely,'' he said. `` They are sometimes beaten and they are sometimes delayed, but the term fraud is wrong.'' `` That the work has proceeded slowly is certainly true,'' <PERSON> Cross </PERSON> said. `` And this is, if you wish, the norm rather than something unusual in a find of this kind.'' The first of the Dead Sea Scrolls, a set of ancient Hebrew texts, were found in a cave in 1947. Some Biblical texts and a collection of laws, stories and poetry were published soon after their discovery. Even more of them, about 400 texts, have yet to be released. `` The problem with these materials is not generally recognized,'' <PERSON> Cross </PERSON> said. `` These are not scrolls which were found intact, the ones that have not been published, but are in literally hundreds of thousands of pieces.'' <PERSON> Shanks </PERSON> said some of the fragments `` are deteriorating so rapidly that if the outside world can not see them soon, it may never be able to see them.'' Cross, however, said that while the material is deteriorating it is `` simply untrue'' that the documents will be lost if not speedily published. `` The early photographs and the rephotographing that is going on now are the way this material will be preserved,'' he said. `` Publication is not going to add anything to the original negatives and the more recent ones.'' The best place for them, he said, would be in a dry place deep underground, like the caves in which they were preserved for centuries. But, he added, `` We ca n't rebury them.''
