<HEAD>Home Sales Fail to Reflect Falling Mortgage Rates in May</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prospective homebuyers failed to take advantage of falling mortgage rates in May when sales of existing homes fell 5.6 percent to their lowest level in 16 months, a real estate trade group reported Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said sales of single-family homes fell last month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.21 million units, down from 3.4 million units in both March and April. The May resale rate was off 11.3 percent from a year ago, the Realtors said, and was the lowest since 3.2 million units were sold in January 1988. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said fixed-rate mortgage interest dropped from 10.97 percent the first week of May to 10.48 percent at the end of the month. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> recently relaxed slightly the grip it has held on the credit supply to restrain the economy and hold down inflation. <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> Vice Chairman <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> on Monday suggested the possiblity of a further interest rate decline when questioned about inflation after addressing the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shareholders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` Well, that's a never-ending process, the fight against inflation,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. `` So, I do n't think we can ever be totally confident. But, I think we are more optimistic about the upcoming period and I think conditions look pretty good.'' Nevertheless, Realtors President <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gribin </PERSON> said of the lag in response to May's falling intest rates: `` Buyers are not going to start flooding the markets the instant mortgage rates start to go down. It takes time for the tide to change.'' But <PERSON> Gribin </PERSON> suggested the pace of existing home sales will pick up in June as people begin to take advantage of lower mortgage rates. The Realtors said the median price of existing homes in May was $ 93,100, up $ 200 from April. The median is the point at which half of the homes sold for more and half for less. The decline in sales was sharpest in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, where there had been steady activity earlier this year. Sales were down 10.1 percent below April to a rate of 800,000 units. The West, which also had been largely unaffected by mortgage rates earlier this year, also posted a notable resale decline to 570,000 units, down 8.1 percent below the April rate. Sales of 590,000 units in the Northeast were 3.3 percent below April. Sales in the South dropped to 1.23 million units, down 3.9 percent from April.
