<HEAD>Officials Underestimating Spread of AIDS, GAO Concludes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-11 pvs, Meanwhile, the ... Cytovene, with 5 grafs
to update with official FDA announcement on drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A report today that federal officials are underestimating the spread of AIDS raises questions about the nation's ability to cope with the crisis, say congressmen who are monitoring the epidemic. A General Accounting Office report says the number of AIDS cases expected to be diagnosed over the next three years has been undercounted by as much as one-third by the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. `` The really frightening aspect of this report is it proves how little we know about the AIDS epidemic,'' Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore., said Sunday He and Reps. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., and <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., requested the `` When these projections of AIDS cases go awry, it undermines research, destroys the validity of our plans for taking care of AIDS victims and conveys a false sense of confidence to our fellow citizens that the AIDS epidemic is under control,'' <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, in a report being released today, estimated that 300,000 to 480,000 Americans will have been diagnosed with AIDS by the end of 1991. This compares with <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s estimated range of 185,000 to 320,000 cases through 1991. `` The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> has done the best they could but they've been underfunded,'' <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today'' show. `` We need a new survey in this country about <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> sexual patterns, which we have n't had for 40 years.'' `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has the best AIDS reporting system in the world,'' Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, assistant secretary of health and former director of the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>, said on the same show. `` That's why more than 60 percent of the cases reported in the world have been reported by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. ... We can always do better, however.'' Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> today announced approval of a drug to treat an eye infection in AIDS patients that can lead to blindness. It is the fourth drug to be approved for treatment of AIDS or an AIDS-related condition. The drug, ganciclovir, has been widely available for several months to AIDS patients with the eye infection, cytomegalovirus retinitis, under a special <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> category called `` treatment IND'' that allows distribution of promising drugs to the gravely ill while safety and effectiveness research continues. About 20 percent of AIDS patients develop the eye infection. <ORGANIZATION> Syntex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, will market the drug under the name Cytovene. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> also announced `` treatment IND'' status for an experimental protein, r-erythropoietin, to treat severe anemia that weakens nearly half of the 20,000 patients taking the anti-viral drug AZT. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the two actions reflect the agency's commitment to getting promising new drugs to AIDS victims quickly. He said that while there still is no cure for the disease, these two drugs and others recently approved for commercial release and treatment INDs can extend and improve the lives of AIDS patients, making early diagnosis more important. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> evaluated 13 national forecasts of the cumulative number of AIDS cases through the end of 1991 and found a range of predictions from 85,000 to 750,000 cases. The report looked only at the number of potential AIDS cases, not the number of people who test positive for the AIDS-causing human immunodeficiency virus but show no symptoms of AIDS. Projections of the spread of acquired immune deficiency syndrome are important because they are used in deciding how much money is spent on AIDS education, research projects and public health care services for AIDS patients. Also, if faulty forecasting is underestimating the heterosexual spread of AIDS, as the report concludes, the result `` may be luring a significant number of Americans into a false sense of security,'' <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> said. Sunday editions of The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> officials acknowledged serious underreporting of AIDS cases but said <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> projections were too high. The report blamed the undercounting on a variety of factors, including the absence of data on the size of risk groups, the definition of what constitutes an AIDS case, reliance on incomplete surveillance data, and the undercounting of heterosexuals at risk. The report said <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> must get more up-to-date and accurate information about the risk groups if it hopes to improve its projections. Earlir this month, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> study also said <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> may be significantly underestimating the number of Americans with AIDS. The study attributed some of the undercounting to affluent victims who are treated discreetly by physicians who do not report cases of the disease. AIDS is spread by close contact with blood, blood products or semen from infected people. Its chief victims are homosexual men and intravenous drug users. As of May 31, 1989, AIDS had been diagnosed in 97,193 Americans, of whom more than half, or 56,468, have died since June 1, 1981, according to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
