<HEAD>R.I. Spill Dispersing; Cleanup Continues in Delaware, Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs with officials saying little oil off Rhode
Island; damage to Delaware River shoreline called minimal. PICKS UP 7th
graf pvs, `Hours after...'; SUBS grafs 15-17 bgng `Elsewhere, contractors
...' with 5 grafs with briefing on Delaware River.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BX1,PX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 420,000 gallons of oil spilled from a tanker off <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> had largely dispersed or evaporated by this morning, officials said. Hundreds of people worked to clean up spills in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Things were `` much, much better than yesterday,'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morin </PERSON>, a state environmental official, said after flying over the stricken <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prodigy </ORGANIZATION>, which ran aground on a reef Friday at the mouth of <LOCATION> Narragansett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, officials also were optimistic, saying the much heavier oil spilled in the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> on Saturday was so congealed in the cool water that shoreline damage was minimal. Workers used rakes to remove football-size, tar-like gobs from the river, where up to 800,000 gallons spilled. As a tropical storm approached <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, crews there brought in `` supersucker'' vacuums to clean up a 250,000-gallon spill near <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Morin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> director of groundwater and wetlands, said he and other officials flew more than 14 miles offshore and found only one small patch of oil about four miles out that he said was unlikely to reach shore. `` I have n't seen it anywhere on the beaches we've flown today,'' he said. Nevertheless, Gov. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> ordered beaches to remain closed today, and a ban on shellfishing remained in effect. Since lobsters, flounders, cod and haddock _ important to the region's fishing industry _ are now laying eggs, it is the worst possible time for an oil spill, said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> of the <ORGAN