00 National Guardsmen, 120 prison inmates and 200 volunteers fought the oil. The oil spread rapidly over nearly 30 square miles. At one point, it threatened <LOCATION> Block </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, a fashionable vacation spot, but this morning officials said that worry had ebbed because the oil was evaporating rapidly. `` You're reaching the point where you're running out of molecules that can go anywhere,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, Chief Warrant Officer <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Meidt </PERSON>. Most of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s beaches reopened Sunday after overnight winds pushed the oil offshore, but the governor today closed beaches nearly to <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. Elsewhere, contractors in the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> hired 255 employees, and <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> agreed to provide 300 National Guardsmen to help remove the heavy fuel oil floating in globs and occasionally washing ashore in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. Federal officials said this morning that shoreline damage was minimal. Coast Guard Capt. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdock </PERSON> said there wo n't be much of a problem unless the oil was somehow warmed to 95 degrees or higher and liquified. The tanker, refloated Sunday, was carrying 18 million gallons of heating oil. Officials said that they were unable to account for at least 800,000 gallons but that the actual spill was probably less. Shoreline contamination was reported from <LOCATION> Ridley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Castle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del. </LOCATION>, about 30 miles to the south. Wildlife officials worked to protect <LOCATI