<HEAD>Algerians Riot Over Prolonged Water Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Residents of the southern Algerian town of <LOCATION> Sud-Aissa </LOCATION> burned buildings in street riots to protest cuts in water service, the <ORGANIZATION> Algerian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported. The most recent water cut, which lasted several days and extended into the weekend, sent 1,500 demonstrators into the streets Saturday to burn public and private buildings in the small town 125 miles south of <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>. Several vehicles, including two belonging to the police, were set ablaze, the news agency reported Sunday. It did not indicate whether there had been any injuries. In April, riots spread throughout <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> because of deteriorating economic conditions and price increases in the North African country of 25 million. The demonstrations led to reforms in <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>'s constitution and the government of President <PERSON> Chadli </PERSON> <PERSON> Benjedid </PERSON>.
