<HEAD>Anderson Reprimanded by Committee of Journalists in Gun Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A committee of journalists reprimanded columnist <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> on Monday for his `` role in bringing a gun into the Capitol'' for a television show on terrorism but did not revoke his press credentials. He rejected the reprimand. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> has said he engineered the plan to smuggle the gun into the Capitol last month to show a need for better security. He did not carry in the gun himself. `` We believe that you abused your privilege as a credentialed member of the daily press gallery, and needlessly jeopardized the relationship reporters have with the Capitol police,'' <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Birnbaum </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>, wrote in a letter to <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. He said the five-member committee, which provides credentials to reporters who cover <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, `` has voted unanimously to reprimand you for your role in bringing a gun into the Capitol last month.'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> responded with his own letter, saying: `` With no disrepect intended, I must reject the reprimand of the standing committee.'' He said he knew that several terrorist leaders were planning to make the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> their target and that the political leaders would be in danger. `` I'm appalled that the congressional leaders whose lives I wanted to protect seem less concerned about the threat to their security than the political embarrassment I apparently caused them.'' During an interview May 24 with Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., in <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s private office, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> pulled from his pocket a gun that had been concealed in his televison crew's The incident occurred during taping for a segment of his TV program and <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> claimed it was to demonstrate security breaches in the building. But it is a felony to bring a firearm onto the Capitol grounds or into any of the buildings, and Capitol police and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney are investigating whether to press charges against <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, said officer <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correspondents </ORGANIZATION> he would not be at their meeting unless <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, the minority leader, were there. They did not appear, though they had initiated the action by asking <PERSON> Birnbaum </PERSON> in a June 6 letter to `` review this serious incident and take sufficient action to deter any future repetition of this act.'' The committee, whose leaders are elected by journalists, was established by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to decide who should work in the press galleries and to allocate space in the galleries. Along with sending a letter of reprimand to <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, the committee voted to revise its regulations so that any credentialed member who disobeys security rules in the future would be subject to suspension. `` When you used your position as a reporter to have a weapon brought into the Capitol, and then produced it in the office of Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> on May 24, you violated the trust that our extension of the credential to you implies,'' said <PERSON> Birnbaum </PERSON>'s letter to <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. `` Therefore we admonish you in the strongest terms.'' While <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> is credentialed, he has not picked up his identification tag and was using a visitor's pass at the time of the incident. He said he entered the Capitol as an ordinary citizen and `` was afforded no special privileges or treatment because I am a journalist.'' <PERSON> Birnbaum </PERSON> said that he did not recommend suspending the investigative reporter because he was not carrying the credential, there was no precedent for such action and `` our own rules are sufficiently unclear that so drastic a step might be misconstrued as the rendering of a judgment by an official press body on the quality of Mr. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>'s journalism.'' Other members of the committee are <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Brenner </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Deibel </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Scripps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorey </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Salt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>.
