<HEAD>Malaysia to Ban Koran With Roman Script</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government will ban versions of the Koran using Roman script, allowing only those in <PERSON> Jawi </PERSON> and Arabic scripts, an official said Monday. <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamid </PERSON> <PERSON> Othman </PERSON>, director general of the Islamic Affairs Division in the prime minister's department, said the ban would take effect in about six months. Under the ban, anyone possessing the Koran in Roman script could be imprisoned for up to three years or fined about $ 1,850, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fatwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which rules on Islamic matters, decided to impose the ban, because the Roman version did not give proper pronunciations. The <PERSON> Jawi </PERSON> script looks like Arabic or <LOCATION> Urdu </LOCATION> script. Islam is <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>'s official religion and about half of its 17 million people are Moslems. The others are mainly Buddhists, Hindus and Christians.
