<HEAD>Thousands of Israeli Moslems Leave For Mecca</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALLENBY BRIDGE, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of white-robed Israeli Moslems crossed this army checkpoint Monday for the annual pilgrimage to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials urged them to help mediate between the Jewish state and its Arab neighbors. `` There has been a lot of hatred, mistrust and enmity,'' Cabinet member <PERSON> Ehud </PERSON> <PERSON> Olmert </PERSON> said at a ceremony marking the pilgrims' crossing the bridge to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> for the trip to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. `` You can serve as a bridge'' between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> on the one side, and <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states and Palestinians on the other, said <PERSON> Olmert </PERSON>, the prime minister's adviser on <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> affairs. But some of the 5,400 Israeli Arabs pilgrims said they identified more with the Palestinians' 18-month uprising in the occupied lands than with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` We are proud of the uprising. It has given us more respect outside,'' said <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Nuseirat </PERSON>, 42, of the northern Israeli village of <LOCATION> Taibeh </LOCATION>. `` We have deep ties to the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> in the occupied territories. It's religion that binds us together, and we are all members of the same nation,'' Nuseirat said. There are 810,000 Israeli Arab citizens, from families who remained in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> when the Jewish state was founded in 1948. About 1.7 million Palestinians live in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, including those who fled <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in 1948 and residents of the occupied lands before they were captured in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. Nuseirat and about 1,400 other Israeli Arab pilgrims, most in white robes and white prayer caps, sat in two dozen buses waiting for a last security check before crossing the <LOCATION> Allenby </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. Women wearing white scarves repacked their belongings after searches by soldiers, reassembling bed rolls and plastic shopping baskets filled with rice, sugar, olives, coffee and tea. About 5,400 Israeli Arabs, up about 400 from last year, are leaving for Mecca via <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> this week. They are scheduled to return by July 21. Mecca is Islam's holiest site, and making the hajj, or pilgrimage, is one of the chief religious duties of Moslems. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, both technically at war with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, first permitted Israeli Arabs to join the hajj in 1977. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> limits the number of pilgrims, and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> only gives exit permits to Moslems who are 30 years of age or older, citing security reasons. `` We are angry about this. In our religion, there is no such thing as an age limit,'' said <PERSON> Yehiah </PERSON> <PERSON> Haj </PERSON>, 31, also of <LOCATION> Taibeh </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Haj </PERSON> made his first pilgrimage last year and said Israeli Arabs attract much attention in <LOCATION> Saudia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. `` When we say where we are from, people gather around. They want to know what's going on in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' he said.
