<HEAD>Fitzwater Says Latest Spills Show Pervasiveness of Problem</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s spokesman accused the oil industry Monday of moving too slowly on oil-spill cleanup technology and said three weekend spills highlight `` the pervasiveness of the problem.'' But presidential press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would not take any direct steps to respond to the weekend spills in <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` The White House does not intend to assume an operational role in oil spills,'' he said. `` We think the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> is fully able and adequate to carry out these responsiblities.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> also ruled out a moratorium on new oil drilling and exploration. `` We have to go ahead with exploration and development of natural resources. We have to have petroleum products for meeting our energy needs,'' he said. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said a `` commanding aspect'' of the latest spills was to show ` the pervasiveness of the problem.'' He said they underscored the need for legislation to better define tanker owners' liabilities He cited legislation proposed by the administration on May 11 to give tanker owners `` first level of responsibility'' for paying cleanup costs. Under the administration bill, tanker owners would be automatically liable for damages from $ 5 million to $ 78 million, depending on the extent of the spill and the size of the ship. A federal fund would be set up to pay cleanup costs over the $ 78 million ceiling, to be financed by a fee of 1.3 cents on every barrel of domestic as well as imported oil. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> last year received reports of 7,500 oil spills, 200 of which required a federal takeover of cleanup operations. `` We feel the industry could do more ... both individual companies and the industry as a whole, particularly in the area of research into better techniques for dealing with oil spills,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` Presumably we have had a lot of experience with oil spills. We know that they are going to occur. We have in place systems to deal with them. But we also know, from recent experience, that there are problems that have to be corrected,'' he added. He said the `` most obvious'' shortcoming is the industry's research and development into better ways to disperse oil spills `` We also find that research has not produced dispersants the way it should. That work is going forward. The sense of urgency I believe is there in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- and -RRB- in the administration. So there's no need to delay development of energy resources, but there is a need to move quickly and effectively on better techniques in dealing with oil spills.''
