<HEAD>Mopping Up Continues As Officials Eye Aftermath</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spills Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Environmental experts said Monday most of the estimated 420,000 gallons of oil spilled into the ocean no longer threatened the shore, and federal officials began a criminal investigation. Only a few small patches of oil could be seen in <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> and along the state's shoreline, state and federal officials said. `` The worst is over,'' said <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Payton </PERSON>, an oceanographer with the <ORGANIZATION> Natonal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's not going to be any more shoreline impacts like there were at the beginning I'm confident of that.'' She estimated no more than 5 percent of the highly toxic oil spilled from the tanker World Prodigy remained floating on the water. The tanker, loaded with nearly 8 million gallons, went aground Friday on <LOCATION> Brenton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION> at the mouth of <LOCATION> Narragansett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> estimated 420,000 gallons spilled. There had been some reports of lobsters killed and several small birds found dead, but officials said those did not appear to be widespread. `` My feeling is that people in <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, scientists included, are being maybe a bit upbeat,'' warned <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sargent </PERSON>, director of the coastlines project at the <ORGANIZATION> Woods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Agents from the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and three other state and federal agencies met with <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGA