<HEAD>Missouri, Kentucky Cases Focus of Supreme Court Ruling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Scotus-Juvenile Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are thumbnail sketches of the two cases in which the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled Monday that states may impose the death penalty on murderers who killed when they were 16 or 17.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Missouri: Heath Wilkins</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Heath </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> was 16 when he stabbed to death a convenience-store clerk as she pleaded for her life. His attorneys described a childhood of abuse, drugs and liquor. His first burglary was at age 7, and at 10 he bought rat poison, tried it on a dog, then put it into Tylenol capsules for his mother and her boyfriend. She secretly emptied the capsules, then made <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> swallow them. In July 1985, <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> plotted the robbery of <PERSON> Linda </PERSON>'s Liquors and <LOCATION> Deli </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Avondale </LOCATION>. He told a girlfriend, another friend and <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Bo </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> about the plan; he and <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> robbed the store while the others waited nearby. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> grabbed <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, 26, and <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> stabbed her in the back and chest. As she pleaded for mercy, he stabbed her in the throat. The robbery netted $ 450, cigarettes, rolling papers, cheap wine and peppermint schnapps. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> pleaded guilty to second-degree murder and was sentenced to life in prison. The two other accomplices were convicted of conspiracy to commit first-degree murder; one got probation and the other was sentenced to 15 years. A state judge is to rule July 26 on <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON>' request for a new trial based on the argument he was not mentally competent at the time of the crime.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Kentucky: Kevin Stanford</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanford </PERSON> plunged into crime at age 9. He was a drug addict at 12, and was arrested for robbery, burglary, assault, attempted rape and other crimes by 17. That's when he raped, robbed and murdered a gas station attendant. <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> came from <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>'s low-income West End, his surroundings modest but hardly desperate. He apparently never knew his father; his mother, a hospital therapist, worked long hours. Until he was 6, he lived mostly with his near-invalid grandmother. He quit school after ninth grade. On Jan. 7, 1981, <PERSON> Baerbel </PERSON> <PERSON> Poore </PERSON>, 20, was alone at a Cheker Oil station next to <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION>'s apartment, working nights to support an infant daughter. <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> and two other teens decided to rob the station. <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON>, 18, sexually abused and terrorized <PERSON> Poore </PERSON> in the bathroom while 15-year-old <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> waited out in a car. <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> then forced <PERSON> Poore </PERSON> into her car and drove with her to a woods, followed by the other two. <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> gave her a last cigarette, then shot her twice in the head. The take was 300 cartons of cigarettes, $ 143.07, two gallons of gas and a gas can. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s case remained in juvenile court and he testified against <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON>, who were tried together in August 1982. <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON> did not face the death penalty because he was n't the triggerman; he was sentenced to life.
