<SECOND>AM-Vegetable Outlook,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Growers Devoting 1.41 Million Acres to Four Major Crops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vegetable processors have contracted to a sharply larger acreage this year to help make up for 1988 drought-shriveled production, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report showed Monday. Overall, growers will have 1.41 million acres devoted to four major vegetable crops in 1989, a 14 percent increase from last year and 15 percent more than in 1987. `` Planted acreage of snap beans is up 22 percent; sweet corn is up 8 percent; green peas jumped 15 percent; while tomatoes increased 17 percent,'' the report said. Vegetables contracted for canning totaled 970,000 acres, including tomatoes, a 13 percent increase. Freezers contracted 441,000 acres, up 17 percent. Reduced production last year because of drought helped boost vegetable prices sharply, including further rises in the first quarter of 1989, according to department economists. Consumer food prices generally this year are expected to rise an average of 4 percent to 7 percent, compared with a rise in 1988 of 4.1 percent. The retail price of processed vegetables by themselves rose an average of 4.8 percent in 1988, compared with a 2.8 percent increase in 1987. This year, according to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> economists, consumer prices of processed vegetables are expected to be 8 percent to 10 percent higher.
