<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are facts and figures on the status of three major oil spills.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>RHODE ISLAND:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The estimated 420,000 gallons of oil spilled from a tanker off <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> on Friday had largely dispersed or evaporated by Monday morning, officials said. The Greek tanker World Prodigy struck a reef Friday at mouth of <LOCATION> Narragansett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. The spill was initially estimated at up to 1.6 million gallons. The light oil had spread over an area of almost 30 square miles by late Sunday. An undetermined number of oil-covered small lobsters and several birds were found dead.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DELAWARE:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil spilled Saturday when the Uruguayan tanker <PERSON> Presidente </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> ran aground in the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Claymont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del. </LOCATION>, was so heavy it congealed into large globs in the cool water. An estimated 800,000 gallons of industrial heating oil was unaccounted for, including an undetermined amount that became mixed with water and remained in the vessel. Some oil fouled shores on both <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> sides of the river, plus some shores upstream in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, but mostly the globs were too large to wash ashore. Tanker was refloated Sunday and taken to a refinery dock to be unloaded.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>TEXAS:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A tug-driven barge ruptured when it collided Friday with a cargo ship in the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> Ship Channel near <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Porte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Channel connects <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. Spill of heavy crude oil estimated at 250,000 gallons. Most of the oil that washed ashore affected industrial property. Wind and waves concentrated most of the oil in a small channel and a third or more of the 6,000 barrels that leaked from the barge had been recovered by Monday.
