PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON> may have become a threat to the established order run by the <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> brothers since the Marxist revolution in 1959. Gen. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> said that after <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON> returned from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> last year, he began spreading lavish gifts around `` in a delirous exercise of self-complacency.'' He said <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON> was trying to create `` an image and ties of personal gratitude with an absolute lack of principle and ethics.'' The government has mounted an intensive public relations campaign against <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON>, describing his alleged corruption in extraordinary detail in <LOCATION> Granma </LOCATION>, the official newspaper of the Cuban <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Granma </PERSON> published the entire text of Gen. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s remarks to the tribunal on its front page on Monday. <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> residents have mobbed news vendors since the scandal broke on Thursday, buying up every available copy of Granma minutes after it hits the streets. In a break from its usual reticence to report on internal affairs, <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON> <PERSON> Latina </PERSON> has distributed extensive reports on the drug scandal. Cuban televison showed film from the closed tribunal on Sunday night, and government radio has run scores of interviews with soldiers and officers who professed outrage at <LOCATION> Ochoa </LOCATION> for betraying the high moral stands of the revolution and the armed forces. <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON> was decorated for his service as a field commander in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> in 1987 and 1988 and is one of only five officers ever awarded the Hero of the Republic of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. Gen. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> on Sunday told the tribunal that <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON>'s actions were `` a stab in the back to the fatherland.''
