<HEAD>Coast Guard Facing Four Major Spills</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The same pumps used to evacuate oil from the <LOCATION> Exxon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> were clearing out the World Prodigy off <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> Monday as the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> found itself dealing with four major oil spills. Officials said a response system that is under review as a result of the March 24 Alaskan spill appears to be working well in handling smaller oil spills in <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. No equipment or personnel had to be moved from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> for the latest spills, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pascoe </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s environmental response branch <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> is paying thousands of workers to clean up oil in the 10-million-gallon Alaskan spill. In each of the latest spills, local <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials were overseeing the cleanup, said <PERSON> Pascoe </PERSON>. But a strike force used in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and based in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> was at work with its pumping equipment in <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Narragansett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> where the World Prodigy ran aground Friday and spilled 420,000 gallons of processed heating oil, <PERSON> Pascoe </PERSON> said. The high-velocity pumps purged the Exxon Valdez of its remaining 40 million gallons of oil a few days after it ran aground in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. The World Prodigy retained about 6 million gallons, which was being pumped into barges. <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guardsmen </ORGANIZATION> and private contractor employees were scooping up blobs of oil from an estimated 800,000-gallon spill from a Uraguayan tanker Saturday in the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. But Coast Guard officials said shoreline damage downriver in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> nd <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> was almost nonexistent because the oil was thick and was not washing up on the shore. In <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> was investigating a collision Friday between the tanker Rachel-B and a barge owned by <ORGANIZATION> Coastal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Towing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. Most of the area affected by that spill was industrial. <PERSON> Pascoe </PERSON> said it was too early for the Alaskan spill to have much impact on the way the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> or other agencies respond to spills. But he noted that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is considering several measures to deal with spills in the wake of the Alaskan disaster, and the oil industry last week announced its own plans for a coordinated response. <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> units throughout the country also are conducting a six-month review of their contingency plans for oil spills. The review is to be completed in the fall. <PERSON> Pascoe </PERSON> said the fact the reviews are under way may have heightened the response of officials to the latest spills, but he said there have been no policy or operational changes since the Alaskan spill.
