<HEAD>Foes Call Death Penalty Ruling `Tragic'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opponents called Monday's <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions upholding the death penalty for retarded killers and some teen-age murderers appalling and tragic, but law enforcement officials hailed the rulings as a victory in the fight against violent crime. `` It is quite appalling that the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> would read the Constitution ... as not banning the execution of children,'' said <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarzschild </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. `` To let society hang children is medieval and barbaric.'' However, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON> said he found the decisions on juvenile killers gratifying. `` In an era of growing concern over the increase and seriousness of violent crime, the court's decision ... reaffirms that state legislators, the juvenile justice system and local juries _ not the federal courts _ can and should decide upon the proper age to impose the death penalty,'' <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON> said. `` Clearly, some 16 - and 17-year-olds in our society are fully mature and capable of plotting and carrying out the most heinous of crimes,'' he said `` The court has obviously responded to society's demand to hold youths who are mature enough to commit horrible crimes responsible for their actions. The court said the Constitution's ban on `` cruel and unusual punishment'' does not prohibit the death penalty for murderers as young as 16, or for retarded adults with the reasoning capacity of young children. The court upheld the death sentences of a <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> murderer who was 17 when he killed and a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> killer who was 16, as well as a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> killer who has the mental capacity of a 7-year-old. `` It now falls to state legislatures to assure that no individual with this disability is ever put to death in this country,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> on Mental Retardation. `` The execution of any such person would represent a tragic injustice.'' <PERSON> Schwarzschild </PERSON> said `` the execution of people who are not fully responsible for their acts is an atrocity.'' <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Raven </PERSON> said his organization was gravely concerned about the court's decision on juvenile killers. `` To give up, with ultimate finality, upon a person even before they emerge from childhood ... is squarely in opposition to the fundamental premises of an enlightened juvenile justice system,'' <PERSON> Raven </PERSON> said. But Missouri Attorney General <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, whose office successfully argued in favor of letting states impose the death penalty on murderers who committed their crimes while 16 or 17, took issue with such concerns. `` I think that's hogwash,'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> said. `` There's a lot of people that say it's going to open the door. That's ludicrous.''
