<HEAD>Savimbi Says Cease-Fire Holding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMBA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> rebel leader <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> appeared before thousands of cheering supporters Monday and said the cease-fire is holding in the civil war and that more peace talks are planned this week. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said at his bush headquarters in southeastern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> that he believes a national unity government can be established by the end of the year, although he set no firm date. `` I am confident the negotiations will bear fruit,'' he said of talks planned this week in <LOCATION> Kinshasa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>, between the Western-backed <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement and the Marxist government of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. `` The Angolan people want peace ... and the <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> delegation is prepared to be flexible,'' he said. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> denied reports that he consented to go into foreign exile. He said he will remain in his homeland as leader of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, known by its Portuguese acronym, <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>. `` A person goes into exile after he's been defeated,'' he said. `` I plan to stay right here.'' Thousands of rebel soldiers and civilian supporters sang, danced and waved red-and-green paper replicas of the guerrilla flag at a parade to celebrate the cease-fire, declared Thursday at a 20-nation African summit in <LOCATION> Gbadolite </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>. `` The spirit of the cease-fire can be considered as holding,'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said. He said isolated skirmishes could break out due to the difficulty of contacting all combatants, but he said he thinks the truce will last. The summit was the first meeting between <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> since the battle for power broke out in 1975 shortly after <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> gained independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. The guerrilla movement controls areas in southeastern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> occupied by up to 3 million of the country's 9 million people. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> and <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> sealed the accord with a handshake and agreed to more talks. Since the handshake, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> radio has referred to <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> as `` <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> president,'' rather than its previous description of him as a `` traitor'' and `` bandit leader.'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON>, meanwhile, said the rebel radio now refers to <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> as `` president'' rather than `` caudillo,'' the <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> word for `` tyrant'' or `` dictator.'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> praised <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> for his `` bravery'' in agreeing to the talks with <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>. `` I want President <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> to succeed,'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said. `` I know he needs time.'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said he expected talks between the two sides in <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> and possibly another <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> summit to review the process in August or September. The Angolan government said during the weekend that the cease-fire was holding. <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>'s chief of intelligence, Gen. <PERSON> Wambu </PERSON> <PERSON> Chindondo </PERSON>, said the rebels declared a halt to offensives in February and that the guerrilla movement had no difficulty abiding by the cease-fire. He said the combined Angolan-Cuban forces appeared to be preparing for attacks but there were no major battles in recent weeks. The Angolan civil war has claimed tens of thousands of lives, and involved several foreign governments including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. In a dispatch from <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> news agency <ORGANIZATION> Lusa </ORGANIZATION> quoted unidentified diplomatic and military sources as saying the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> pressured <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> to attend the <LOCATION> Gbadolite </LOCATION> summit and accept the Angolan peace plan. According to <ORGANIZATION> Lusa </ORGANIZATION>, the sources said <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> at first refused because of `` internal discord'' within <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sese </PERSON> <PERSON> Seko </PERSON> was `` obliged to contact <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, in order to ensure the success of the summit.'' The cease-fire follows U.S.-brokered regional peace accords <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> signed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in December with <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Under the accords, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> agreed to allow <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s southern neighbor, <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, independence under a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan and halt aid to <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON>'s guerrillas. In exchange, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> agreed to a phased withdrawal of its estimated 50,000 troops backing dos <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>' government <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> was not party to the agreement.
