<HEAD>Member of New Collective Leadership Pledges `Unambiguous Reform'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, HUNGARY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Rezsoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON> said Monday he and the other three members of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s new collective leadership will work together for `` unambiguous reform.'' <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON>, the new party chairman, said the four leaders chosen over the weekend have equal responsibility, but in matters of party policy he is `` first among equals.'' Creation of the four-man presidium by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> appears to strengthen the reform wing and limit the power of <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, the party general secretary, who also is a member. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, who replaced longtime party chief <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> 13 months ago, has resisted numerous demands from reformers that he resign. Also on the new leadership team are <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON>, the party's leading reformer, and reform-minded Premier <PERSON> Miklos </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nemeth </PERSON> insisted at a news conference Monday that each of the four had equal power. `` It is not a mathematical formula of three plus one,'' <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON> said in a clear reference to the reformers and <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>. `` It is not a question of where we've been, but where we are going. The party wishes to become a more unambiguous reform party.'' He said the party had chosen to dissociate itself from `` extremes.'' <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON> said: `` A real compromise was achieved. The important matter is the unity of views, and not the differences.'' He said peaceful transition to `` democratic socialism'' and a multiparty system should not lead to a `` power vacuum.'' `` A country should not run loose,'' <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON> declared. `` It is important to govern.'' Prominent members have expressed concern that a split might cause the party to disintegrate. <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON> has said repeatedly that none of the political groups springing up in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> is ready to assume power. <PERSON> Nemeth </PERSON> said, `` It would be wrong to define unity by the former criteria,'' under which the leadership presented a unifed platform. `` Everyone is a boss in some way'' in the new presidium, he said. As <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON> explained it, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> would be responsible for the entire party apparatus and <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON>, the chairman, would handle the party's domestic and foreign relations <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON> has been proposed as the party candidate for president of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> when the post is created. The new presidency would have far greater powers than the current ceremonial office. In the new leadership `` everyone supports reform,'' <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> told the news conference, with debate centering on the type of reform and the pace at which it should occur.
