<HEAD>Sakharov Urges Cut in Soviet Army To Promote Disarmament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIK A. WOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet dissident <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said Monday that trimming the Soviet military and halving enlisted men's service time would have `` a colossal effect for world disarmament. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said the number of Soviet army officers should be reduced at a slower rate `` with the view of setting up an all-professional army.'' He told reporters at the <ORGANIZATION> Nobel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> that arms reduction should be <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s major foreign policy priority. The institute is home of the committee that awarded him the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, 68, arrived from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Sunday for his first visit here since winning the prize for his human rights activities. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said the Soviets were being `` pragmatic'' in their guarded response to the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> government's crushing of the Chinese democracy movement and the death sentences for Chinese students. He pulled a paper from his pocket that he said was a telegram he sent to world leaders. It said, `` Now is not the time for cautious, pragmatic reactions.'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said that despite the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s removal of its last troops in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in February, `` the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> still has considerable influence in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and ought to reduce it.'' He spent eight years in internal exile in <LOCATION> Gorky </LOCATION> for attacking the mass Soviet military intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in late 1979. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, a renowed physicist who helped develop Soviet nuclear capability, said he favors continued use of nuclear energy, but recommended that power plants be built underground. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Yelena </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON>, were invited by the Oslo-based <ORGANIZATION> Norwegian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> and the Humanities; the <ORGANIZATION> Nobel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Michelsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intellectual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bergen </LOCATION>. Soviet authorities would not let him come to <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> to accept the 1975 Nobel prize and Ms. <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON> received it on his behalf. `` She came home full of warm feelings for <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. Now I'm extremely happy to be in this house which has so often been in my thoughts,'' <PERSON> Sahkarov </PERSON> said He is to meet Prime Minister <PERSON> Gro </PERSON> <PERSON> Harlem </PERSON> <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Thorvald </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON>. He also will address scientists, visit research institutes and attend a human rights seminar. The Sakharovs earlier visited the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and will proceed to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>.
