<HEAD>Text of Wright's Statement on Decision to Quit and Not Seek Re-Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wright</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a text of former Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s statement on his decision to resign his <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> seat effective Friday and not seek re-election Since announcing that I would retire from the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> at the end of this month, I have received thousands of written and verbal requests from people in my district imploring me to reconsider. Some have spoken of writing my name in on the special election ballot, and some others even have begun circulating petitions to place my name on the ballot. Naturally I have been moved by such gracious and spontaneous expressions of support. I did not encourage these entreaties, but out of profound respect and affection for the wonderful people who have been coming to me, I did not peremptorily dismiss their ideas. I heard them out. As deeply as I appreciate the devoted friendship which impels these sincere petitions, I must conclude that I was right in announcing my retirement from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Independent polling data have made it very clear that I could be re-elected. These demonstrations of strong bipartisan support are truly gratifying, but I feel that I probably have done as much good as I can do in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> at the present time and should look to the next phase of my life. It is best for the institution and best for the people whom I've served that I step aside now and make room for others Thirty-four and a half years is a very long time, and I have been richly blessed. To seek and gain the splendid honor of a public endorsement one more time would be vainglorious. To do so without intending to serve for a prolonged period would be pointless. To postpone the moment when another may begin would be a disservice. I do not foreclose the possibility that at some future time and some other way I may again be of service to our nation, but not in elective office. As for now <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> and I are ready to enjoy a period of private life. I will not be inactive, but I hope to be selective and pursue a slightly less hectic pace than at present. I have received perhaps 65 or 70 speaking invitations, for example, and have accepted five or six. I am also considering some limited business and professional relationships and some invitations to write. I will have an office in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. If I should live to be 100, I shall never cease to be grateful to the people of my area and to my colleagues in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who have made it possible for me to do whatever good I've been able to do for our country and to have the joy of doing it.
</TEXT>
