<HEAD>Justice Minister Says Deportations Can Help Put Down Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to ADD first reference to Meridor.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The justice minister Monday said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> should deport more Palestinians to help crush the revolt in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Meridor </PERSON>'s suggestion is among tougher measures to handle the 18-month uprising proposed by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials and criticized by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and human rights organizations. `` I think deportation is serious but must be used, I would say perhaps even more that what has been done until now,'' <PERSON> Meridor </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think it's an effective punishment when we have appropriate evidence,'' he said. Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> has recommended speeding up deportation procedures as well as demolishing more homes of Palestinians suspected of anti-Israeli activities and lengthening the term security suspects can be detained without trial from six months to one year. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and human rights organizations say all three methods ignore international conventions on the treatment of people in occupied lands and violate due process of law because suspects have no chance to go to court. The justice and defense ministries Sunday set up a joint committee to devise tougher measures to put down the uprising. <PERSON> Meridor </PERSON> told the radio about 50 Palestinians have been deported since the start of the uprising and nearly 300 houses have been demolished or sealed. Also Monday, the body of a woman suspected of cooperating with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities was found in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reports said. She had been beaten to death, they said. Palestinians said <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khadi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanaan </PERSON>, 30, had been accused of collaborating with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s secret police, but an army spokesman said police believe the killing was criminal. Ms. <PERSON> Kanaan </PERSON> was the 68th suspected collaborator killed by Palestinians since the uprising began in December 1987. The unrest has killed 536 Palestinians and 23 Israelis. A suspected collaborator killed Sunday initially was identified by <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reporters as <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON> <PERSON> Salhab </PERSON>, 21, but police Monday said <PERSON> Salhab </PERSON>'s father reported his son was alive. The victim's head had been crushed, and police said they still are trying to determine his identity. Meanwhile, Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> must present a united front on its peace plan. `` Though it may be difficult and painful, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> must declare and demonstrate to one and all, friendly and unfriendly, that she is not divided and that her mission of peace is sincere and real,'' <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> said, speaking at a <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> graduation ceremony. Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> has proposed holding elections in the occupied lands to select <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> representatives to open negotiations on an interim peace agreement with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Hard-liners in his right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc oppose the plan, saying it could lead to formation of a Palestinian state. <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> also said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should stand behind <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` This is a time of testing for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, testing whether we are prepared to take this important step in the pathways of peace, and we must not fail,'' <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> said.
