<HEAD>Chicago Merc Should Do Better Policing Job, Says CFTC Staff</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and other futures markets should do a better job of cracking down on high-pressure telephone sales tactics at member firms, the staff of the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The staff report praised the exchange for responding to earlier suggestions for improvement, but said more needs to be done to ensure that `` investigative procedures adequately address the issue of detecting abusive oral sales representations.'' One of the biggest complaints of securities and futures customers after the October 1987 stock market crash was that they had been talked into making unsuitably speculative investments without being properly warned of the risks. The staff of the commission, which regulates futures markets, praised the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> for starting a program of interviewing customers to make sure futures brokers do n't use sale pitches designed to override risk disclosure documents provided to customers. However, it said the exchange should routinely conduct the interviews in a more systematic and timely fashion. Specifically, the commission staff said the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> did a poor job of investigating a particular firm, which it did not identify, that had attracted an unusual number of customer complaints. `` The -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- Division -LRB- of Trading and Markets -RRB- believes that the exchange's investigation was not concluded -LRB- in a -RRB- timely -LRB- manner -RRB- and should have included certain additional procedures'' such as an attempt to uncover high pressure sales tactics,'' the agency's report said It also said that the exchange's requirement that most actions by staff investigators be authorized by an internal committee `` may unnecessarily prolong an investigation.'' <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yemma </PERSON>, a spokesman for the exchange, said the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> disagreed with the commission's assessment of that particular investigation. `` We believe our efforts were timely and thorough and we will attempt to bridge this gap with the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. However, he said the exchange intends to adopt a commission suggestion that it work more closely with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and will adopt an invesigatory technique used by the association. The association sometimes has its investigators pose as customers as a way of uncovering sales abuses. In another recommendation, the commission said the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>'s member firms should do a better job of supervising sales personnel who were hired away from other firms that got into trouble with regulators. `` Members of the -LRB- Mercantile -RRB- and of other exchanges as well have employed, and in some cases even, recruited ... -LRB- employees -RRB- of firms subject to commission enforcement proceedings or disciplinary actions for sales violations,'' the report said. <PERSON> Yemma </PERSON> said the Mercantile would adopt the recommended procedures for monitoring such employees. In general, he said the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> believes the commission report was favorable. For instance, it praises the exchange for more than doubling its audit staff from 16 in May 1985 to 35 in January 1988. Futures markets regulation has become a particular focus of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> since the disclosure in February that the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> had conducted a two-year undercover investigation of alleged abuses. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are questioning whether futures exchanges' self-regulation system is working and whether the commission is providing effective oversight of the system. The legislative scrutiny will likely come to a head this fall because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must reauthorize the commission before Sept. 30 or the agency will go out of business.
