<HEAD>Nelson Out as Immigration Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, criticized earlier this year in a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> audit, was replaced Monday as head of the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the department said. Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> announced in a brief statement that he was appointing <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buck </PERSON>, deputy <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> commissioner, as acting head of the service to replace <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, who resigned. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> declined to say why <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> was being replaced before a permanent successor is found. But a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said officials were concerned about the overall management at <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>, which was criticized in the audit ordered earlier this year by <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>. Officials were particularly concerned about the agency's budget because <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> _ as a lame duck _ had no incentive to control spending, the source said. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, a holdover from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, has been privately criticized by department officals, who have long signaled that he would be replaced. His resignation has been pending since the start of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration but was not accepted until this weekend, <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> McNary </PERSON>, the chief executive of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, is expected to be nominated by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to fill the post. <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> said senior officials of the agency were not informed of <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s decision to replace <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> with Buck until 10:30 a.m. Monday, about the time the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> issued its public announcement. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> said <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, who was in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, was first advised last Wednesday that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would be accepting his resignation and was formally informed of the action by telephone on Saturday. The audit said accounting, management and administration were in disarray, citing a growing backlog of cases awaiting adjudication. It also noted that INS Western regional officials had chartered jets to fly to conferences when commercial flights were available. More recently, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> raised the ire of <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials by approving a trip to the National Sheriff's Association convention in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> of 19 officials of his agency. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> was forced to cancel the trips of all but three or four after the department issued an order `` to curtail the number of attendees traveling'' to conferences and meetings. This episode, the source said, raised concerns in the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> about <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>'s commitment to controlling spending. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> defended his agency against criticisms in the audit, which he called `` grossly deficient.'' The audit noted that the agency had spent $ 1,500 for an oil portrait of <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials were also privately critical of a videotape tribute to <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> that <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> produced at taxpayer expense. In his statement, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> `` has led the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> through difficult times.'' During his tenure at <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> oversaw the amnesty program for illegal aliens that was enacted by the 1986 Immigration Reform and Control Act. Rep. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, D-Conn., who chairs the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> immigration subcomittee, said in a statement that he `` wished Commissioner <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> well'' but added that `` I have long felt that a change in leadership was needed'' at <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> `` But more than new leadership, what is needed is a complete reorganization of the structure if the functions now collected under the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> are to be performed effectively.''
