<HEAD>Power Cuts Expanded in Uruguay; General Strike Called</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL GIANELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state power company said Monday that electricity shutdowns in this capital city of 1.2 million people will be doubled to six hours a day. It put most of the blame on drought. <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>'s biggest labor coalition meanwhile announced it will stage on Tuesday its eighth general strike against the government of President <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON> to press demands for wage and pension increases. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrato </PERSON>, president of the state <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transmission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said electricity in <LOCATION> Montevideo </LOCATION> and several other cities will be cut from 5 p.m. to 11 p.m., adding, `` Since records have been kept, there has not been so severe a shortage of rain.'' Much of the electricity in this Oklahoma-sized, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> nation of 3 million comes from hydropower. The lack of rain has idled 13 of the 14 turbines of the Salto Grande complex on the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, a major power source. For weeks, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> bought electricity from neighboring <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. But this week <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, which has been having its own troubles, is scheduled to resume power cuts itself. A bit more than 8 -LCB- inches of rain have fallen this year, <PERSON> Serrato </PERSON> said, less than half the normal amount. Drinking water is being rationed in the small city of <PERSON> Melo </PERSON>. Throughout <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, grazing land has dried out and water is being trucked in for livestock. The general strike was called by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, which is demanding a pay increase of about 30 percent starting July 1. The current minimum wage, set in February, is about $ 70 a month. The increase would apply to many of the approximately 260,000 state employees, who make up about one-quarter of the total work force. Private sector companies raised wages by about 25 percent for the March-June period. Inflation for 1989 is projected at 80 percent. Union leaders also want an increase in retirement pensions and oppose proposals to sell state companies which might result in layoffs or higher prices for services.
