<HEAD>U.S., Soviets Begin New Talks on Monitoring Underground Tests</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: LEADS throughout, CORRECTING Hiroshima blast kilotons, UPDATING
with White House statement. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GEV1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet negotiators resumed talks Monday on monitoring nuclear tests, and both sides predicted agreement soon. They are drafting new monitoring provisions for two superpower treaties of the 1970s, still not ratified by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, limiting military and other nuclear explosions to 150 kilotons. One kiloton has the force of 1,000 tons of TNT. The bomb dropped on <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, in 1945, originally reckoned at 20 kilotons, had an explosive force of 12 or 13 kilotons. The goal is to get <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ratification, which was withheld because of concern that the limits could not be enforced. Talks resumed after a six-month recess caused, in part, by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration review of arms control and security policy. Monday's meeting was held at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Mission in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, between delegation chiefs <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Palenykh </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> has said the purpose of the new negotiations, expected to last five to six weeks, is to produce complete agreements. <PERSON> Palenykh </PERSON> said there is `` a good basis for reaching practical results within a short time.'' They said a verification plan for the 1976 Peaceful Nuclear Explosions Treaty is virtually complete but some work remains on how to prevent cheating on the 1974 Threshold Test Ban Treaty. Both sides are to be allowed various methods of measuring the power of explosions, including on-site checks at each other's testing grounds Future negotiations are intended to produce more agreements to limit nuclear tests and ultimately prohibit the. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has urged <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to join in a test ban, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says tests will be necessary as long as its military strategy includes reliance on nuclear weapons. Talks on nuclear testing are separate from U.S.-Soviet negotiations on reducing long-range nuclear arsenals, which resumed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> last week. Presidential press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that a realistic verification plan is crucial to success of the new talks on monitoring tests. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> approach to these negotiations complements our efforts to reach agreements that will strengthen our security and enhance stability,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said in a statement. `` A priority for these step-by-step talks is to complete protocols to provide for effective verification'' of the two treaties. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ratified neither treaty because `` they were not ratifiable in their original form.'' `` Our approach to these negotiations is based on a realistic approach to our security,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` As long as we must rely on nuclear weapons, we must continue to test to ensure their safety, security, reliability, effectiveness and survivability.''
