e forest that the federal government was bound to recognize. `` It is inappropriate for a decision of this magnitude, involving approximately 5,440 acres of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> land, to have been based on a dearth of written independent agency analysis and supporting agency documentation,'' the report said. `` No record exists which suggests that the Office of Surface Mining conducted a thorough analysis'' before ruling that the company had a legal right to strip mine for coal, said the report. The company has submitted an application for state mining permits covering 180 acres. Spokesman <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Ambs </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> `` will probably act on it sometime before the end of the summer.'' <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said Monday a deputy assistant secretary was reviewing the <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> determination `` to see what prompted the decision, how it was based,'' and he could not comment on the report. The congressional probe was conducted at the request of Rep. <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahall </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, chairman of the He has asked <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary Manual <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> to freeze activity on all pending coal rights claims until there's a federal standard in place. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said a reply probably would be ready next week. The <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, part of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, and the congressional investigators contend the Office of Surface Mining should have followed state standards since there's no federal standard governing companies that buy previous owners' mineral rights and apply to mine on land like national forests. An unsigned, undated Office of Surface Mining memorandum provided to the investigators said turning down the coal company was `` probably the most defensible position legally.''
