<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorneys for death-row convicts blasted a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling Monday that allows the execution of murderers who committed their crimes as young as 16, while prosecutors applauded the decision. `` In my opinion, it's utterly barbaric to execute any 16 - or 17-year-old,'' said <LOCATION> Sapulpa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, attorney <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Ravitz </PERSON> His client, <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Sellers </PERSON>, was convicted in 1986 of killing his parents and a convenience store clerk in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> at age 16. <PERSON> Ravitz </PERSON> argued that his client was under Satan's influence. Asked about the decision, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Nance </PERSON> said, `` I think we're pleased from the attorney general on down.'' In 5-4 votes, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said the Constitution's ban on cruel and unusual punishment does not prohibit execution of older juveniles or adults with only the reasoning capacity of children. In a second instance, however, the court ruled that convicted murderers have a right to demand that sentencing juries and judges consider mental retardation as a possible mitigating factor. The juvenile killers ruling affects about 25 of the 2,200 death row inmates across the nation. There are at least 11 states with one or more inmates under a death penalty for crimes committed before they were 18, according to state officials. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> topped the list with nine inmates, followed by <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> with four each. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> apparently drew the line for capital punishment at age 16 last year when they voted 5-3 to throw out the death sentence of an <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> murderer who committed the crime when 15. The ruling will probably not affect <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> because she was 15 when she stabbed a retired <PERSON> Gary </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, Bible teacher to death, said her attorney <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Touchette </PERSON>. Miss <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>'s case has drawn international attention and a call for clemency from Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II. In <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, lawyer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON> reacted with sadness to the court's ruling. <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON> was the trial attorney for <PERSON> Cleo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lecroy </PERSON>, who was convicted in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in the 1981 shooting deaths of a couple camping in rural <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lecroy </PERSON> was 17 at the time of the crime. `` Even countries such as <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> have recognized that killing their children is not something that people ought to do, and I'm sorry that in this country we do n't feel the same way, do n't have the respect for our kids' lives,'' <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON> said <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Snurkowski </PERSON>, who is in charge of death appeals for <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON>, said the ruling seemed `` to affirm the system that we currently employ.'' In its decision, the high court upheld the death sentence of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> inmate <PERSON> Heath </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON>, who was 16 when he stabbed a <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> area liquor store clerk to death in 1985. <PERSON> Michele </PERSO