<HEAD>Mayor Returns Home Despite Alleged Threat by City Airport Commissioner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoemehl </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and his family returned home under increased police protection after fleeing their house for 48 hours because of threats allegedly made by the city's airport commissioner The commissioner, <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON>, faces two misdemeanor counts of third-degree assault against <PERSON> Schoemehl </PERSON>. <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON> allegedly made the threats because of ordinances adopted last week that sharply curtailed the duties of his ex-wife, city License Collector <PERSON> Billie </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON>. The mayor kept up his schedule over the weekend despite the problems, going to meetings, a high school reunion and a Jefferson Day rally, aides said. The <PERSON> Schoemehl </PERSON> family returned home Sunday night. `` He felt threatened,'' Deputy Police Chief <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauer </PERSON> said. `` We were concerned with the mayor's fears. I had no assurance from -LRB- Luther -RRB- <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON> that this was over.'' <PERSON> Schoemehl </PERSON> said police made the decision Friday to increase the number of his bodyguards from one to four. He also decided to move his family to a safe place, as he has done in the past during protests and demonstrations in front of his house. Meanwhile, the transfer of most of <PERSON> Billie </PERSON> <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON>' duties to other municipal agencies began. <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON>, whom <PERSON> Schoemehl </PERSON> appointed airport commissioner, coordinated the mayor's 1985 re-election campaign on the city's predominantly black north side <PERSON> Schoemehl </PERSON> said <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON>' threat was expressed to aides <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Sortino </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> `` in a very hostile, very vulgar, very aggressive way'' after <PERSON> Schoemehl </PERSON> signed ordinances stripping Ms. <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON> of most of her duties. The city aldermen drafted the ordinances on the basis of State Auditor <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>'s report that Ms. <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON> had failed to collect millions of dollars in revenues due the city. On Friday, the aldermen voted 16-13 to reduce Ms. <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON>' staff from 54 employees to three. Supporters of Ms. <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON>, who is black, contended that the ordinances were racially motivated. <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON>, who was released from a police holdover cell shortly before midnight on Friday, could not be reached for comment on Monday. He said over the weekend he had `` no quarrel'' with <PERSON> Schoemehl </PERSON>. <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON> has a July 6 court date scheduled to answer the misdemeanor charges. Also Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> refused to grant Ms. <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON> an injunction that would bar the takeover of her office. Her appeal followed a circuit judge's rejection of the same request. Ms. <PERSON> Boykins </PERSON> also faces a felony-drug charge in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, that stems from her arrest near there last fall.
