 to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. He called for `` a more creative sharing of global responsibilities,'' and praised the Japanese for shouldering more of the cost of keeping <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops in the country _ about 40 percent. And, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> soon will be the largest donor in the world of overseas development assistance. Yet <PERSON> Mitsuzuka </PERSON>, stressed the need for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> `` to maintain a strong political, economic and military presence and commitment to the region.'' Turning to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> concluded the country clearly had decided to abandon its isolation from regional progress but the pace of political change did not match the aspirations of the people. Defending <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy against calls for sterner measures in response to the violence, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said `` we have acted in a measured way.'' He said it would be a mistake to dismantle the relationship the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> built up over two decades with the Communist government in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. However, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said, Americans and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government will stand for democratic values. And, he said, `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s rendezvous with freedom, like its rendezvous with the advancing nations of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. can not be long delayed.''
