<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An explosion aboard a train in the suburbs of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> killed 20 people and seriously injured 11, an offical reported Tuesday. The official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported that an on-the-spot investigation showed the explosion was caused by dynamite. The official of the <ORGANIZATION> Shanghai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> called it an accident and said the blast happened at 11.13 p.m. Monday -LRB- 10:13 a.m. EDT -RRB- in <LOCATION> Songjiang </LOCATION> <LOCATION> county </LOCATION>, 18 -LCB- miles southwest of the city. He said the No. 364 train was on its way to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Hangzhou </LOCATION>, 112 miles to the southwest. It was scheduled to reach <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> at 00:08 a.m. Tuesday. He said the blast occurred in the No. 7 seated compartment of the train but could not give details. The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, reported that 20 people died, 11 were badly hurt and an unknown number of passengers were slightly injured. He was unable to give the capacity of the train or the compartment. According to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the explosion occurred in a toilet in the front of the compartment. The Japanese <ORGANIZATION> NHK </ORGANIZATION> television station reported that the interior of the train was severely damaged but not burned. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said the vice mayor of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ni </PERSON> <PERSON> Tianzeng </PERSON>, had arrived at the scene to organize rescue work. Six people died in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> when a train smashed through a barricade set up by demonstators pressing for democratic refor