<HEAD>Peruvian Army Patrol Kills 42 Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, PERU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An army patrol battled leftist rebels at their remote highland stronghold and killed 42 of them in some of the worst fighting in the rebels' nine-year insurgency, a military official said Monday. The military refused to provide information on army casualties. The troops and Shining Path rebels fought Sunday evening near the village of <LOCATION> Pampaccori </LOCATION>, 40 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION>, a military spokesman said on condition of anonymity. The military spokesman said troops also captured a large number of weapons and `` subversive propaganda.'' He said it was one of the biggest losses of life suffered by the <ORGANIZATION> Shining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION> in their nine-year-old fight against the government. The <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION> region, 235 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, is the birthplace of the Shining Path insurgency and remains its stronghold. The guerrilla organization began its fight against the government in May 1980 after 10 years of grass roots organizing among Indian peasants in this impoverished region. Since then the violence has spread throughout the country, and more than 15,000 people have died in clashes between troops and guerrillas, as well as in rebel attacks. There has been a recent surge in rebel activity, and analysts say the stepped-up attacks are intended to sabotage municipal elections in November. In violence Monday, two policemen were killed and four were missing after 50 Shining Path guerrillas Monday ambushed a truck carrying six policemen in a mining province in the highlands, police said. The guerrillas hurled sticks of dynamite and opened fire with machine guns during the ambush, which occurred close to a copper-mining complex near <LOCATION> Huancayo </LOCATION>, 140 miles east of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, police said. Last week Shining Path rebels ambushed an army convoy in the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle near <LOCATION> Aguaytia </LOCATION>, 270 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, and 20 rebels and 15 soldiers were killed in the fighting.
