<TEXT>
 Do n't expect to read about <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention in `` The <ORGANIZATION> Rolling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illustrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> History </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Roll'' _ they're not even mentioned And do n't look for <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention in `` The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'' _ they never had a hit single. While reunions of The Rolling Stones and The Who make headlines, <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention quietly tours the country by trailer, appearing in small clubs. But since four -LRB- soon to be six -RRB- young English musicians formed the band in 1967, <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention has produced some of the finest folk-rock of the past two decades. `` If you're asking whether I thought the band would still be traveling about in the late 1980s, the answer would be no,'' said guitarist <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicol </PERSON>, an original member who helped put <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention back together in 1985. Their early records were heavily influenced by the Beatles and the <ORGANIZATION> Byrds </ORGANIZATION>, with spirited harmonies and a tight rhythm section. Besides <PERSON> Nicol </PERSON>, the group featured the brilliant guitar playing and songwriting of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, and the songwriting and soulful vocals of <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Denny </PERSON>. `` You had a band at the end of every street, and for most people it was a phase they went through,'' <PERSON> Nicol </PERSON> recalled. `` The unlucky ones got caught on the treadmill. We wanted to get off the treadmill.'' By their fourth album, 1969's `` <LOCATION> Liege </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Lief </PERSON>,'' <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention was recording traditional English songs and making greater use of the mandolin and fiddle, instruments that had been rarely used in a rock' n' roll format. They built a small, but devoted following with the originals `` Come All Ye'' and `` Meet on the Ledge,'' the traditional `` Matty Groves'' and covers of <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON>'s `` I'll Keep It With Mine'' and `` Percy's Song.'' `` I think that the Byrds had taken their roots and made it viable encouraged us,'' <PERSON> Nicol </PERSON> said of the American folk-rock group. The group went through several personnel changes and by the early'70s, <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Denny </PERSON> had left to pursue solo careers. The band struggled without them, eventually calling it quits in 1979. But in August 1980, <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention _ minus <PERSON> Denny </PERSON>, who died in 1978 _ reunited for a concert in <LOCATION> Cropredy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Encouraged by the response, the band played again the following summer and now headlines an annual two-day festival of folk-rock and traditional music. They began recording again in 1985, with <PERSON> Nicol </PERSON> and two other <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention veterans _ bassist <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Pegg </PERSON> and drummer <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattacks </PERSON> _ forming the core of the group. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> was well established as a solo star so guitarist <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Allcock </PERSON> and fiddler <PERSON> Ric </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> were recruited. `` The three of us had gotten on terribly well,'' <PERSON> Nicol </PERSON> said. `` We'd known <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> for years, he was very enthusiastic and really wanted to play with us. <PERSON> Ric </PERSON> was also a fan. We rehearsed three days and found out it was going to work.'' They have since released four albums: `` <PERSON> Gladys </PERSON>' Leap,'' `` Expletive Delighted,'' `` In Real Time'' and, most recently, `` Red and Gold.'' <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> Convention has also toured extensively, using mostly new material as well as `` Matty Groves'' and `` Meet on the Ledge.'' `` It's impossible to say what a typical <LOCATION> Fairport </LOCATION> audience is because they all look different,'' <PERSON> Pegg </PERSON> said. `` We get 17 - and 18-year-old kids who have discovered the music for the first time and people in their 50s A lot of our audience are more familiar with the new stuff.'' The title track from `` Red and Gold'' was written by <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> McTell </PERSON>, a friend of the band who learned that <PERSON> Cropredy </PERSON> had been the site in 1644 of a bloody battle during the English civil war. The album also includes a cover of `` Open the Door Richard''; a pair of instrumentals written by <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>, `` The Rose Hip'' and `` The Battle''; and a traditional ballad, `` The Beggar's Song.'' `` It's just surprising when you come up with traditional songs that people have n't heard before,'' <PERSON> Pegg </PERSON> said. `` The best ones have been recorded, if not by us, then by other bands like <PERSON> Steeleye </PERSON> <PERSON> Span </PERSON>. They got about 50 percent of the really good songs and we got the rest.''
