<FIRST>a i AM-Mexico-Abortion Adv03   06-26 1072</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Abortion, Adv 03,1111</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, July 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arrest of Women Focuses Attention on Illegal Abortions in Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 9th paragraph.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Abortion is a secret act in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Federal law makes it a crime, except in cases of rape or if the woman's life is endangered. The Roman Catholic church calls all abortions a sin. Yet Mexican health officials estimate that one in 10 pregnancies end that way every year. The estimate may be low. The last time an attempt was made to change the law, in 1979, pro-abortion lawmakers were beaten in the streets. Their photographs appeared on posters calling them `` assassins.'' Marchers denounced them as `` communists.'' But pro-abortion activists are ready to make another try, and anti-abortion activists are girding for battle. `` There is pressure by a lot of leftist groups to legalize abortion,'' said <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> <PERSON> Limon </PERSON>, leader of the Pro-Life organization. `` But we are ready to fight this dangerous movement.'' The pro-choice side has been encouraged by news and other accounts of the arrest, interrogation and alleged mistreatment of eight women after they had abortions. They are also watching closely the abortion debate in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The arrests took place March 16, when <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> and nine other women were returning to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> from an illegal abortion clinic in the adjacent state of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Three police intelligence agents stopped their van at gunpoint. `` Bitches!'' <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said they shouted at them. `` Whores! Assassins!'' They were taken to an intelligence police jail where they were later joined by a doctor, two nurses and a receptionist who were arrested at the clinic. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>, 27, a schoolteacher's wife and mother of a 3-year-old daughter, said she and the others were slapped and pistol-whipped. She added that they could hear the screams of their elderly doctor being tortured with electric shocks. Then, she said, they were interrogated about their abortions. The women also were subjected to what <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> called `` painful and humiliating'' pelvic examinations in the presence of three men who made sexually disparaging remarks. `` I felt like I was going to faint because of the abortion, the emotional stress and the fact I had not eaten since the day before,'' <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> recalled in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. After 14 hours, the women were released without being charged. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> police spokesman <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Algorri </PERSON> confirmed that uniformed intelligence agents arrested the women. In an interview, <PERSON> Algorri </PERSON> handed over a copy of the arrest report, saying, `` That's all the information I have. The report did not say what happened after the arrests. <PERSON> Algorri </PERSON> would not comment on <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>'s charges that the women were mistreated. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said she went public with her account at the urging of fellow members of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and because `` my life is threatened anyway.'' Pro-choice activists are hoping to rewrite the 1931 law that outlaws abortion except in the cases of rape or endangerment of the woman's life. `` I have been involved in the women's rights movement here in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> for 15 years and I've only seen two cases where judges approved the abortions,'' said <PERSON> Heather </PERSON> <PERSON> Dashner </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> activist. The penalty for women who have illegal abortions is an automatic suspended sentence, but doctors who perform them can lose their medical licenses. Federal deputy <PERSON> Amalia </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> plans to propose clarifying guidelines for legal abortions when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> reconvenes in the fall. If there is enough public support, <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> will propose legalizing all voluntary abortions. The last such proposal, made in 1979, created an uproar before dying in committee. `` I think <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has changed,'' <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> said. `` There is more tolerance. A more open way of thinking.'' Still, she said, a fight to legalize abortion would be tough. Both the Catholic church and the vocal Pro-Life group, which oppose all abortions, are powerful in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Pro-Life leader <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> said he is ready for battle. During an interview AP in his office, <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> pointed to 7-foot-high stacks of anti-abortion petitions the group will begin circulating this summer. By September, Pro-Life plans to present <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> with the signatures of at least 5 million people opposing abortion, he said. Some pro-choice activists believe <PERSON> Pro-Life </PERSON>'s vocal anti-abortion campaign fostered the climate that led to the arrests of <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> and the others. <PERSON> Rosario </PERSON> <PERSON> Villalobos </PERSON>, who accompanied <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> during her abortion and who also was arrested, said that the week before <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> had called for a crackdown on abortion clinics. `` I do n't think it was a coincidence,'' <PERSON> Villalobos </PERSON> said, but <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> denied any responsiblity for the arrests. `` The newspapers said we were starting another Inquisition,'' <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> said. `` Although abortion is a crime, we condemn the torture, the physical aggression against the women.'' A crackdown on clinics wo n't stop women from ending pregnancies, federal deputy <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> said. Most women in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, where an unskilled female worker makes about $ 3.50 a day, can not afford the $ 125 to $ 400 that clinics charge. Instead, they perform their own abortions or seek help from a midwife, nurse or friend. Mexican women fling themselves down stairs, use coat hangers, drink risky herbal brews or douche with cleaning chemicals. They sometimes bleed to death afterward, <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> said. While the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> estimates the abortion rate at 10 percent of 2.4 million pregancies annually, a recently published government study estimated 700,000 abortions are performed nationwide annually. The estimate was drawn from a survey showing 70,000 women were treated for post-abortion complications at Social Security hospitals in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in one year. The study, which did not survey private hospitals and clinics, indicated that women with abortion-related complications are the third most common Social Security hospital patient. It said six of every 100 such patients die. Although birth control was legalized in 1972, unwanted pregnancy is common. Many women do n't use birth control because of ignorance or because they are ashamed to ask for it. Some live in rural areas where contraceptives are unavailable. Most women undergoing abortions have at least three children and can not afford another, <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> said. Or they need to work, she said. Both public and private sector employers give female job applicants pregnancy tests. Pregnant applicants are turned away; pregnant workers are fired. `` Lots of <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> women have abortions,'' <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said. `` The only difference is that I talked about it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, July 3</NOTE>
