<HEAD>With BC-APN--French Revolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Quotations inspired by the French Revolution: `` Man is born free, and everywhere he is in irons.'' _ <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Rousseau </PERSON>. `` History is little else than a picture of human crimes and misfortunes.'' _ Voltaire `` I am the rage of the people.'' _ <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Marat </PERSON>, who also urged the crowd to `` cut the thumbs off aristocrats who conspire against you; split the tongues of the priests who have preached servitude.'' `` It would be unwise to appeal to the people, because virtue has always been a minority on this Earth.'' _ <PERSON> Maximilien </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Robespierre </PERSON>'s argument against putting the execution of <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> XVI </PERSON> to a public vote. `` I can not shed the blood of my people.'' _ <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> XVI </PERSON>'s repeated excuse for not using force against the crowd. `` Let them eat cake.'' _ <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Antoinette </PERSON>'s alleged reply when told the country people had no bread. -LRB- The actual quote was `` Qu'ils mangent de la brioche'' _ let them eat breakfast buns. -RRB- `` O, Liberty! How they have duped you.'' _ Madame <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Roland </PERSON>'s last words, addressed to a plaster statue of liberty set up near the guillotine `` It is a far, far better thing that I do, than I have ever done; it is a far, far better rest that I go to, than I have ever known.'' _ <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> Carton, going nobly to the guillotine in the <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickens </PERSON>' novel `` A Tale of Two Cities.''
