<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 locator
map, 1 logo.    EDITOR'S NOTE _ No phones, no TV, no store, yet, remarkably,
a post office. But if it's gold you're after, and boom-town lore, Flat,
Alaska, is the place to go. One native son, at age 71, is still digging.
   ___</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JULES LOH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLAT, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You can count the year-round population of this town on the fingers of one hand. They are <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sherri </PERSON> <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON> and their three children. In the summertime, the four months of thaw in interior <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, the population swells to a grand total of maybe 30. These are gold miners drawn back as irresistibly as the migrating swallows. They come to work their old mining claims, to see anew the bedazzling flashes of yellow among the gravel in their gold pans. The lure must be irresistible because even in summer Flat has none of the amenities you might expect in any <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> village, however small, with a certified <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> post office. Not one store. Not one cash register. Not one telephone. `` I am the federal presence here,'' says <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON>. `` I am the postmaster. Here is the post office.'' He shows, proudly, a one-room building of about 10 feet by 15 feet that he explains was once a liquor store he restored according to government specifications, complete with a Zip code and a flag. `` I fly the flag by the rules,'' he says. `` I raise it at dawn, which here in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> happens in April, and I take it down at sunset, in September.'' Correction. Flat, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, does have a store. It is padlocked, but its goods are still on the shelves, unsold. The last sale was about 1942. One of the unsold items is a brand-new dog sled. It also has a bank, likewise padlocked. Inside is a roll-top desk, its pigeonholes full, a green visor and sleeve garters in one drawer, a locked vault with who knows what in it, and a set of brass scales that weighed 1.7 million ounces of gold. Flat was one of this frontier state's boomingest gold boom towns, now frozen in time but still breathing. Its gravel streets and byways are strewn with carcasses of cars and trucks and mining debris dating from the 1930s. `` When those people all left,'' says <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON>, `` I guess it was too much trouble to take them out.'' <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON>, a mechanic, drives a'38 pickup truck he made to run like a jeweled watch from salvaged parts. It would indeed have been at least as much trouble to take all that stuff out as it was to haul it in. Flat was named for nearby <LOCATION> Flat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>. It might as easily have been named Otter for another nearby creek. -LRB- Or <PERSON> Poorman </PERSON>, for yet another, although that would not, over all, have been accurate. -RRB- It is out in the wilderness 275 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> as the crow flies. As the hungering miners found their way here when gold was discovered by a prospector named <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Beaton </PERSON> in 1908, the route was much longer. It required riverboats up the <LOCATION> Kuskokwim </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, then up the <LOCATION> Iditarod </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> to a landing place, then eight miles overland to the gold fields of Flat. A town of about 6,000 sprang up at the landing place, Iditarod, and the gold rush became known as the Iditarod Stampede. Nothing remains of Iditarod, only weathered skeletons of a few buildings. One of them was Tootsie's, a house of ill fame. A bathtub from the collapsed rubble of <PERSON> Tootsie </PERSON>'s now resides in the home of <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sherri </PERSON> <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON> at their home in Flat, which they built and furnished themselves. `` Is n't it something, look at those clawed feet,'' says Mrs. <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON>. `` If only it could talk.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON> remembers Tootsie's. In fact, <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON> has a remarkable memory for every place and every excitement in Flat since he was born here in 1918 in a cabin on <LOCATION> Otter </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>. He is the son of an ambitious immigrant who heard about the Iditarod Stampede, got in on it, worked for wages, bought a claim and sent for his wife in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> is the result. He, at 71, and his wife, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>, and any of their four grown children who can make it, return to Flat every summer, with the swallows, to take out of their now extensive land holdings whatever gold a mom-and-pop operation, as he calls it, can yield. `` In the early days we took 6,000 ounces a year,'' he says. `` We do n't even try for that now, but it's still worthwhile.'' You bet. Gold appears daily in his sluice, and two years ago he unearthed a 28-ounce nugget. At the going price of gold, that alone is worth about $ 8,000. `` Well,'' says <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON>, `` because it's a nugget and not dust, and it fits just right in the palm of your hand, it's probably worth at auction 10 times the price of gold. Some Texan would pay that to make it into a belt buckle. `` Oh, yes, we still have it,'' he says. `` You're never broke if you have a little gold put aside.'' But <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON> did n't make it only on gold. Working for his father as a boy he had to straddle, like a horse, a huge and heavy cannon-like hose nozzle used to bust up gold-producing earth with a high-pressure stream of water. It was hard work, and dangerous. He figured there must be a better way. So he invented one, and patented it. If you have seen a fireboat at work or a ladder truck with a mounted nozzle you have seen <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON>'s invention, a water cannon with even higher pressure but small and safe and easy to aim. `` I designed it for miners,'' he says, `` but it was firefighters who wanted it the most.''
</TEXT>
