<FIRST>s a BC-APN--ReportFromAlaska-II Adv09-1stAdd   06-26 0866</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Report From Alaska-II, Adv 09-1st Add,0894</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>FLAT, Alaska: the most.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON> left school in the 11th grade, never went to college. Yet the knowledge of geology and mining he picked up on his own is so recognized that he has served for years in the winter months as a consultant to mining companies, inspecting potential digging sites around the globe. He could have made a fine living at that alone. It is n't need or greed, he says, that draws him and his wife here every summer from their comfortable winter home in <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Their home here is typical of an <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> mining camp It is small, tin-roofed, its plumbing uncertain, its dooryard cluttered with old wagon wheels, moose antlers, remains of mining equipment. `` It does n't have all the comforts,'' he says, `` but we actually look forward to coming back every year. `` We like the isolation. We like getting out and working with our hands. If the ballgame on TV, or the Sunday paper, or the movie house are n't all that important to you you would understand.'' The now-empty town also brings back vivid memories for <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON>. He remembers the day <ORGANIZATION> Wiley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> crash-landed here in 1933. A snapshot of <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON> with the pioneer aviator hangs on his wall. He remembers catching fish as a boy, selling them to the miners to relieve their diet of moose steaks, and of the excitement when a bear would wander into town. He remembers the Fourth of July bashes at the recreation hall that lasted three days. The hall remains, decorated with 48-star flags and a fine upright piano. The piano needs tuning. And he remembers the great Black Bear gold robbery, Flat's only recorded crime. `` It was set up by the mail carrier who delivered the gold by dog sled, $ 120,000 worth, and by a prostitute known as Black Bear _ her sister was called The Cub _ and by her procurer. `` They got caught, the gold was recovered, the mailman turned state's evidence and went free. The other two were tried in Fairbanks. The jury set them free, too ... `` Black Bear and the procurer later made a fortune in bootlegging and went off to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to raise racehorses.'' <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON> saw the boom end and Flat's terminal illness set in. Flat became inaccessible except by airplane, the old Iditarod road rendered impassable by neglect. Small operators could n't meet the bottom line. For excitement in Flat today, the biggest attraction would be <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON>'s workshop. It is truly a wondrous place. Machinery from another age still functions _ lathe, drill press, saw, forge _ turned to life by a single motor and a dozen flapping belts. `` This is where I spend most of my time,'' he says. `` It's my playground.'' Anything busted, <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON> can fix. The very isolation of Flat, not to mention all that abandoned machinery to play with, was what prompted the Keplers to buy one of its forsaken houses seven years ago to use for summer outings. They lived in <LOCATION> Aniak </LOCATION>, a small village 75 miles southwest, the closest place from here where people live. He worked there as a commercial pilot and airplane mechanic. <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON> is 35. The two Kepler boys are 12 and 9 and the girl is 2. `` When the postmaster job opened up three years ago we decided to come out here and stay permanently. To us, this is paradise. I have plenty to keep me busy.'' What do you do in winter? `` Mostly cut wood.'' Wood fuels the <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON> furnace and the kitchen stove. A diesel generator provides electricity for the refrigerator, but kerosene lamps serve for much of the lighting. Do the children like the life? `` They love it. The other day <PERSON> Sherri </PERSON> and I were discussing the possibility of the post office closing down and us having to leave. The boys said they would stay without us.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON> teaches the children by correspondence, not unusual in the Alaskan outback. She uses books and lesson plans provided by the state. She talks to a correspondence teacher twice a week, by radio. `` Both boys test well above their grade level,'' she says. Every three or four months <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> cranks up his airplane and the Keplers go shopping in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. They have their supplies mailed back, which gives <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON> a little business at the post office. His other postal business is mainly forwarding mail in winter to the miners who keep Flat as their permanent mailing address. Unlike <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON>, who has a regular second home, most of the others go off to various sunny places to spend their gold. The mail plane arrives three times a week, even if there's nothing to deliver Flat happens to be on the way between other more populated mail drops and it is n't much trouble to make one more landing. Besides, Alaskans have a tradition of seeing to one another out in the <PERSON> bush </PERSON>, especially during the dark, harsh winter. `` Drop us a Christmas card,'' says <PERSON> Kepler </PERSON>. `` We're always glad to hear from the outside.'' Five people there. That's all. Their address is Flat, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, 99584.
