<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 He's a self-styled `` bad-boy bureaucrat,'' decisive and outspoken, a maverick fond of his adversaries, a conservative aboard a motorcycle. <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON> is in charge of the nation's most volatile immigration district. In dealing with Haitians, Cubans, Nicaraguans and others flooding into <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, he keeps his office door ajar and his phone lines open and runs his district like a benevolent despot.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s immigration director who sometimes seems to be a branch of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government unto himself, angrily called a Haitian exile leader about the sign someone erected outside the <LOCATION> Krome </LOCATION> alien detention center. It read: `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Concentration Camp.'' `` Does that bother you?'' asked the Rev. <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jean-Juste </PERSON>, the exile leader. He was assured in the strongest terms that the sign did bother <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>, a fervent admirer of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and traditional <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> values, albeit he sometimes dresses in black leather and zips around town on his motorcycle. The next day, the sign had been replaced. The new one: `` <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>'s Concentration Camp.'' <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON> had to laugh when he called <PERSON> Jean-Juste </PERSON> after that one. <PERSON> Jean-Juste </PERSON> was laughing, too. The priest, who has been the outspoken leader of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s Haitians for a decade, may not like <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>'s policies, but he likes <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON> `` We are friends and enemies at the same time,'' <PERSON> Jean-Juste </PERSON> explains. `` We tease each other and laugh together, but when we are on business we are both devils.'' For his part, <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>, who recently rebuked <PERSON> Jean-Juste </PERSON> publicly for calling him `` Mr. <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>,'' promises to invite his friend <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> to his going-away party when he retires later this year after 22 years of federal government service. `` The <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Show </PERSON>,'' the ongoing exchanges between two of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s most public figures, is symptomatic of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> in the six years since <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON> returned to his hometown from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>, the self-styled `` bad-boy bureaucrat'' is in charge of the nation's most volatile immigration district. In dealing with Haitians, Cubans, Nicaraguans and others flooding into this immigrant city, he keeps his office door ajar and his phone lines open and runs his district like a benevolent despot, quite unlike the nation's 34 other immigration districts. `` I think <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON> has been a breath of fresh air,'' says <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurzban </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> attorney who recently filed the latest in 10 years' worth of lawsuits challenging <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> treatment of Haitian immigrants. `` The <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> INS </LOCATION> district office has for a long time been a hotbed,'' says <PERSON> Verne </PERSON> <PERSON> Jervis </PERSON>, chief <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` It's such an international city there are an awful lot of forces at work there. It takes a real juggling act to try to carry out the immigration law.'' Under <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jervis </PERSON> says, the `` INS in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> probably has more support there than ever before. His openness, the access to his office are the highest they've ever been. A number of people here at <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> headquarters certainly view him as a little bit of a maverick, but if you can do that and maintain a semblance of control and order you can get away with it.'' The 100,000 or more Haitians in the area detest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interdiction of Haitians at sea and what they see as unfair and even racist treatment. While they do n't necessarily buy <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>'s explanation that he's simply upholding the law and defending the nation's borders, many Haitians admire his gestures of humanity, such as his 1984 order sending immigration officers to <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> to fetch a 9-year-old Haitian boy who was deported while <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON> was on vacation Cubans, who with more than 800,000 in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> constitute the largest <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> community anywhere except the city of <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>, have feted <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON> and admire his anti-communism. The immigration director says that if he were president, he'd have the Marines landing on <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s beaches tomorrow. Nicaraguans, more than 100,000 strong in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, like <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>'s aversion to sending them back to what he considers a hostile, sometimes brutal government. And many in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s other Hispanic groups like <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>'s `` caudillo'' - style forceful personality and decisiveness <PERSON> Rivkind </PERSON>, the 59-year-old son of <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> immigrants loves his job, the latest in a long series of federal positions. A high school dropout, he became a master's laureate, Korean War veteran and former <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> hotelier, vice cop, and county police patrolman before becoming a career federal bureaucrat. Most of his 22 federal years have been in the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in various roles, but he still recalls grimly a few months working in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, which he found stifling.
