<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.)</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> has worked as an advertising copywriter, a stand-up comic, a variety show writer-performer and even as a regular on <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s popular television sitcom in which he played <PERSON> Gordy </PERSON> the weatherman. But in his more than 20 years in and out of show business, the broad, powerfully built actor never appeared in a Shakespearean play. That changed recently with his portrayal of Sir <PERSON> Toby </PERSON> <PERSON> Belch </PERSON> in `` Twelfth Night,'' the opening production of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Shakespeare Festival's annual summer sojourn in Central Park. And <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> has found himself in a high-powered company of movie and theater names that includes <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldblum </PERSON>, <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Pfeiffer </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Mastrantonio </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Hines </PERSON>, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>. The actor tried out for the role at the urging of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a veteran of the Shakespearean repertory and one of the best Othellos of recent years. They were sitting in a trailer last year while working on the <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> movie `` Coming to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' when <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> told him, `` If you do n't try <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>, it will just loom as a bigger and more insurmountable obstacle to you. So you just might as well go ahead and take your best shot. Treat it as you would another play.'' `` I had auditioned him before for another play and did n't give him the role,'' recalls <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Papp </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Shakespeare Festival. `` But I thought, ` Gee, he's an interesting actor with an imposing figure and good clear speech.' I told him, ` You should look at Shakespeare's plays because there are many roles you could play.''' After reading parts of `` Twelfth Night'' for <PERSON> Papp </PERSON> and director <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Guskin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> got the role of fun-loving, high-spirited Sir <PERSON> Toby </PERSON>. `` My biggest concern was that I did n't develop an affected accent,'' <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> recounts. <PERSON> Amos </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, did n't start out to be an actor. His big dream was to play football, but nothing came of it. His acting career did n't get going until he moved to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` My entree into show business came because of my writing. During the day, I was working for an advertising agency in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. At night, I was moonlighting on a local television variety show called ` <PERSON> Lohman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barkley </PERSON>' as a writer-performer. We'd do 90 minutes of contemporary comedy and satirical bits.'' Out of that job came a position as a staff writer on `` The <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Uggams </PERSON> Show,'' a short-lived variety show on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> in 1969. On it, <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> helped write what he calls a forerunner of today's situation comedies about middle-class blacks. It was a 15-minute segment called `` Sugar Hill,'' in which Miss <PERSON> Uggams </PERSON> played the wife, <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilpatrick </PERSON> her husband and <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> her brother. `` ` Sugar Hill' taught me a great deal about the structure of situation comedy,'' he says now. `` So that later, when I got involved in performing in a situation comedy, I felt I had a slight edge on some of the other actors.'' His job on `` The <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Uggams </PERSON> Show'' won <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> a role the following year on a new comedy series starring <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. His role of <PERSON> Gordy </PERSON> the weatherman was his first national recognition. <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> had studied acting at a small theater in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> but he likes to think he honed his acting skills working as a stand-up comic in clubs in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> in the late'60s. `` I was n't very good,'' he says now. `` But it's the best training any actor can get, particularly if you use your own material. Then you can gauge whether or not your perception of what's funny is funny to the general public.'' <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> lived in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> for about 15 years before coming back to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He was able to support himself by occasional television series like `` The Tim Conway Comedy Hour'' and `` Future Cop'' as well as commercials. But he returned to the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> seven years ago to do more theater. `` I had started to loose my hustle,'' he says. `` I'm not the kind of guy who can just lie by the pool waiting for my agent to call.'' Last year, <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> became artistic director and artist-in-residence for a theater located in the <ORGANIZATION> Grant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Plainfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, after its mayor, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, asked him to do a few fund-raisers. He also staged the theater's first offering, `` Forever My Darling,'' a play by <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>. It takes place in the 1950s and concerns four black women who want to become the first female rhythm and blues singing group. <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> has even optioned the movie rights. Work on commercial projects like the upcoming <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallone </PERSON> movie `` Lock-Up'' gives <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> the financial freedom to spend more with his fledgling theater. `` I think I'm pretty much living the ideal life _ staying here in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, so I can be close to my theater, doing, I hope, one picture a year and as much stage work as possible,'' he says. `` That's the best of both worlds.''
