<HEAD>N'DJAMENA: in 1983.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Reports still crop up periodically, however, of skirmishes between government troops and what are described as `` rebels.'' On April 13 the government announced it had put down a rebellion and that three prominent members of <PERSON> Habre </PERSON>'s administration had fled. Information Minister <PERSON> Adoum </PERSON> <PERSON> Moussa </PERSON> <PERSON> Seif </PERSON> said in a recent interview that the April 1-2 incident occurred when the government uncovered a scheme to smuggle arms to Libyan-backed rebels based in western <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. London-based <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> issued a report June 22 saying that at least 100 people arrested in the incident `` may face torture and illegal execution.'' <PERSON> Moussa </PERSON> <PERSON> Seif </PERSON> said `` a number of people were taken in for questioning'' but added that he believed most had been released. Chadians still wonder how long it will be before their future can be unlinked from the plans of Col. <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> leader. Since <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> came to power 20 years ago, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> has been enmeshed in <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION>'s internal affairs, supporting a rainbow of anti-government factions and tendencies over the years. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> publication on aid to <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION> says 7,000 Libyan troops remain in the <LOCATION> Aouzou </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, a 45,600-square-mile area between the two countries occupied by <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> since 1973. The publication adds that <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION>'s `` continued resistence to Libyan aggression helps contain <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>'s expansionist ambitions, curb its aggression and terrorism and reduce Libyan prestige and influence in sub-Saharan <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION> is strategically situated between <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> to the north and <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> to the south and between <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> west </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> in the east. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has backed <PERSON> Habre </PERSON> ever since <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> sent troops into <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION> in 1980, furnishes military aid to <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chadian </LOCATION> military personnel train in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Habre </PERSON> says, a committee of leading Chadians was putting the finishing touches on a draft constitution that he hoped would be put to a vote before the end of the year. The document, he added, would `` provide a more solid basis for democratic rights in <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION>.'' Despite economic problems, some Chadians are optimistic. Among them are <PERSON> Abdel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamid </PERSON>, a 20-year-old shepherd, and his grandmother, <PERSON> Fatima </PERSON>, who look forward to the paving of a road running out of <LOCATION> N'Djamena </LOCATION>. The house from which they make their living selling goat cheese is on the road 12 miles northwest of the capital. `` There's no point in moving to town to sell because then people wo n't think our cheese is fresh,'' <PERSON> Hamid </PERSON> said. `` So when the road is done, people can come to us all year round and not worry about the rains.'' Even in <LOCATION> N'Djamena </LOCATION> the streets turn to mud in the rainy season. Health is another area where international aid has come into play. Dr. <PERSON> Issaline </PERSON> <PERSON> Greindl </PERSON>, a Belgian specialist in tropical medicine, is using computers in a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> University-sponsored project to identify <PERSON> Chad </PERSON>'s major health problems and allocate resources. `` In 1985 no one even knew how many health facilities there were in the country,'' she said, `` but now we are receiving about 310 standardized reports a month which represents about 90 percent of the facilities.'' <PERSON> Chad </PERSON>'s basic health problems are fevers, including malaria, respiratory problems and diarrhea, either avoidable or treatable with minimum infrastructure and medication. The average life expectancy still is in the mid-30s, but in statistical health reports anyone who survives past the age of 5 is considered an adult.
