<TEXT>
 `` True Believer'' -LRB- RCA-Columbia Home Video. VHS-Beta, $ 89.95. Rated R -RRB- `` True Believer'' is fun to watch. Unfortunately, it is not believable. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> plays, with his trademark intensity, <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, a pioneering civil rights lawyer who lost his 1960s spirit on the way to the'80s. He finds himself defending mostly drug dealers, and defending himself for doing so. Along comes a young lawyer, <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> -RRB-, who worships <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>'s earlier work, and an 8-year-old murder case in which the defendant might actually be innocent. <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> is reluctant to take the case, and <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> sneers, `` It was close, huh? We almost defended someone who was n't a drug dealer.'' But <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> plunges into the case, and he also finds he's fighting public corruption and various urban evils. The problem with the movie, directed by <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON>, is that instead of taking a close look at <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>'s disillusionment, or at the relationship between <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roger </PERSON>, `` True Believer'' takes the easy way out and goes for the thrills. For starters, the old murder is recreated, <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> is beaten up by a phony white supremacist, and there's a crazy and dangerous chase through a plumbing supply factory. On the good side, the ending is clever. <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> is fine, as is <PERSON> Yuji </PERSON> <PERSON> Okumoto </PERSON> playing the convict and <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> as a private detective. _ By <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> MacVean </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
