<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Museums Adv07-09   06-26 0944</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Museums, Adv 07-09,0967</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, July 7-9 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Theme Parks May Become Museums of the Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REBECCA MARTIN EVARTS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Museums of the future will have to draw more on Walt Disney than the Renaissance if they are to attract visitors, ensure sources of funding and survive competition from theme parks. `` Museums must change from self-centered to client-centered environments,'' says <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>, director of the Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civilization </ORGANIZATION>. `` They must market themselves not only as educational but also as meaningful leisure-time activity.'' <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> was one of half a dozen experts who spoke at a recent symposium on museums sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Caixa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pensions </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> and the Cultural Olympics, part of the 1992 Summer Olympics organized by the city of <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION>. People already spend more time on visits to theme parks than on trips to museums _ an average of eight hours as compared to 50 minutes, according to statistics provided at the symposium. But interest in museums appears to be on the increase, said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON>, director of the European Museum of the Year Award. He added, however, that government and foundation funding, on which so many museums depend, is shrinking as public budgets are tightened and costs rise, forcing them to become more self-supporting. Museums of the future will have to borrow techniques from the successful theme parks such as extensive sensory stimulation through lights, graphics and color as well as live performances, constant change and updating of attractions, film presentations on giant screens and attractive boutiques selling related merchandise. But museums need not sacrifice their traditional role of educating and providing well-researched and accurate information, <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> said, when improving on attention to the needs and interests of their visitors. Many museum curators would put up enormous resistance to such changes, he acknowledged. `` They have comfortable niches there, and they do n't like the earth trembling under their feet,'' <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> said. `` But I think the future is equally bleak if they do n't respond because their funding will shrink every year, and eventually they'll be running empty museums with no operating budget.'' <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. King, a specialist in American popular culture at <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Thomas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jefferson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said part of the change will require museums to fuse popular culture with the elite culture that has been their traditional domain. In order to attract visitors inside, the experts said, museums of the future will have to offer greatly expanded leisure facilities such as full-service restaurants, theaters, conference facilities and reception rooms big enough to accommodate weddings or perfume and other marketing launches. And they will have to be visually exciting and welcoming, rather than monumental and intimidating. Visitors reared on television will be more readily drawn to exhibits where information is displayed on TV screens than on printed labels, and video-computer hookups will be used to allow museumgoers to request additional information that is specifically suited to their interests. Because visitors will be able to control the information, museums will be able to present several interpretations of an exhibit or object, permitting the viewer to come to his or her own conclusions. Science museums, maritime museums and museums of human civilization have been among the first to make use of theme park techniques. At <ORGANIZATION> Barcelona </ORGANIZATION>'s Maritime Museum, housed in the 14th century Royal Shipyards building on the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> waterfront, the 180 symposim participants were able to see some of the principles of the modern museum put into practice. For example, the recent remodeling is concentrating on highlighting valuable but poorly lighted exhibits such as the life-size replica of the <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s flagship in the 1517 Battle of <ORGANIZATION> Lepanto </ORGANIZATION>, with halogen focus lamps or fluorescent strip lighting that draws the visitor closer to the objects. The three-year-old City of Science and Industry in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Villette </ORGANIZATION> neighborhood was billed by its president <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Lesgards </PERSON> as a `` cultural enterprise'' offering the visitor the opportunity to simulate flying an <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> jet, watch a living fetus as it develops or climb inside the Ariane rocket. If this fails to hold one's interest, the visitor can stroll the 136 acres of park surrounding the museum, visit one of the four bars or three shops, change money at the bank, play the discovery-through-play Inventorium for children or do some research with 190,000 reference works. But directors and curators of fine and decorative arts museums have been slower to welcome the Disney-like atmosphere into their marble halls. `` Art museums still contrive to make visitors feel that they are studying for an examination or should be,'' said <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON>, who is no friend of theme parks. He believes the museum of the future will have to become a grassroots social center where the atmosphere surrounding the objects may be more important than the objects themselves. In <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>'s view, the art museum of the future will have to pay more attention to creating a context for the art and to revealing the codes of meaning contained in the work of many artists, especially contemporary ones. `` One of the most effective ways of doing that is to have presentations that look through the eyes of the artist,'' he said. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Samper </PERSON>, senior director of government and media relations for <LOCATION> Colonial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION>, said most museum people resent the theme park as an interloper. `` For them, the real thing is the real thing,'' he said. `` But like detente, it -LRB- the theme park -RRB- must be recognized. We must adapt our activities to make the best of our assets while keeping up with the competition.''
