<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Bill Anderson Swears Off Songs Glorifying Drinking</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Veteran TV and country music entertainer <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, whose wife was almost killed in a traffic accident, says he will never again perform songs about alcoholic beverages. <PERSON> Becky </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, 43, suffered brain damage and was given just a 50-50 chance to live after her car was struck head on by a truck driven by a drunken driver in 1984. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> recounts the incident, and several other personal setbacks, in his new autobiography `` Whisperin' Bill.'' The book, published by <ORGANIZATION> Longstreet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, takes its title from <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>'s nickname. The 461-page book marks another career milestone for <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, who has been a Grand Ole Opry singer, award-winning songwriter, soap opera actor, network game show host, record producer and businessman. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said his wife's accident, from which she has almost fully recovered, has made him realize the danger of drinking and driving. He's sworn off performing songs about drinking, tunes that are a mainstay of country music. `` This has really opened up my eyes to the fact it is very real,'' he said. `` I do n't think before this happened that I was as sensitive to it as I am now. Before, I thought it was just something you sang about and you kind of lived your life as you wanted to. `` Now, I will not sing a drinking song.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Andersons </ORGANIZATION> filed a $ 4 million civil lawsuit after the accident. A <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> jury awarded them $ 1.2 million, but a judge reduced the award to $ 825,000. At the time, the $ 1.2 million was the largest amount ever awarded in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>. `` The whole thing that happened to her was so senseless,'' the 51-year-old <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said in an interview. `` It did n't have to happen, yet it did. I ca n't blame it on anything other than the fact he -LRB- the other driver, celebrating his 18th birthday -RRB- was drunk.'' The accident happened after <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> had enjoyed one of the most successful and diverse careers among <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> entertainers. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> had been co-host of the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> game show `` The Better Sex,'' had appeared periodically for three years on the soap opera `` One Life to Live'' and also acted in television's `` <PERSON> Alias </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>'' and `` The Men.'' He appeared frequently on other TV game shows such as `` Hollywood Squares'' and `` The Match Game.'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> had recorded more than 40 country music albums and won more than 50 awards for song writing. He had appeared regularly on the Grand Ole Opry since 1961. But the accident was n't the only tragedy faced by the <ORGANIZATION> Andersons </ORGANIZATION>. Daughter <PERSON> Terri </PERSON>, now 28, was diagnosed as having cancer, he lost millions as an investor in a restaurant chain and his own health declined because of a debilitating back problem that kept him on pain medication for months. `` These things kept happening and you wake up every day and hope the last straw is on the camel's back and nothing else will happen,'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. Finally, life is looking up again. The accident and recovery strengthened his strained marriage. The restaurant chain is on the rebound and doctors are optimistic that the cancer in <LOCATION> Terri </LOCATION> was caught in time. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, whose best known songs are `` Still'' and `` City Lights,'' said writing the book was therapeutic. `` When everything came down as hard and fast as it did, I had so much built up it just had to come out,'' he said. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said the adversity `` made me realize how blessed I had been all my life, that I really had lived a charmed life up until then. It made me thankful and more grateful for that. You take things like good health for granted. `` I think the biggest effect overall was in my priorities,'' he said. `` Things that I thought were important were not and things I did n't think were important were more important than I had ever realized, such as my family. `` I had put career ahead of family at times, but I do n't think I'll do that any more. `` I learned about determination, especially from watching what <PERSON> Becky </PERSON> did -LRB- during recovery -RRB-. There never has been a human being more determined.'' In writing the book, he learned quickly that it's more work than composing a song. `` You write a song and you write one page and you're finished. With a book, you're just getting started.'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said he got some good advice from fellow Grand Ole Opry star <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, who also recently wrote an autobiography. `` She said when you mention frying the onions, you have got to make them smell the onions.''
