<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>At the Movies: ``Do the Right Thing'' ^By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 When <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> released `` She's Got ta Have It,'' about a sexually independent young woman, <PERSON> Spike </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> was lionized as the leader of a new wave of independent filmmaking. He had made the 1986 lusty black-and-white movie for an amazing $ 175,000. He spent millions more for `` Do the Right Thing,'' and with this frank, realistic and brutal portrait of racism and its byproducts, the brash young filmmaker has entered the mainstream. Race was not an issue in `` She's Got ta Have It.'' In his last film, `` School Daze,'' <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>' biggest grosser for 1988, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> was strident and polemical in his treatment of racial issues. But in `` Do the Right Thing,'' he allows the movie itself to unravel and define bigotry. The theme for the movie's title comes from a speech made by the late black activist <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> X </PERSON> in December 1964: `` Racism is a human problem and a crime that is absolutely so ghastly that a person who is fighting racism is well within his rights to fight against it by any means necessary until it is eliminated.'' <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> X </PERSON>, and the late Nobelist <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, both play an indirect role in the movie, which takes place in a lower-middle-class neighborhood in the <LOCATION> Bedford-Stuyvesant </LOCATION> section of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. It is a longing to include photographs of the late civil rights leaders on a `` wall of fame'' in a pizza parlor run by an Italian that sparks a tragic racial confrontation. The Italian owner has only the pictures of white Italian-Americans on his wall, such as <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sophia </PERSON> <PERSON> Loren </PERSON>. It is a sweltering summer in <LOCATION> Bedford-Stuyvesant </LOCATION>. Perspiration runs freely, as do fire hydrants and tempers. <PERSON> Sal </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Aiello </PERSON> -RRB- and his two sons, <PERSON> Vito </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pino </PERSON>, open their pizzeria to start a new day. Da Mayor -LRB- <PERSON> Ossie </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> -RRB-, an ancient resident who spends his time washing down the yesteryears with a bottle of beer, sweeps up; <PERSON> Mookie </PERSON> -LRB- Lee -RRB- arrives in <LOCATION> Dodgers </LOCATION> shirt -LRB- they were once the <ORGANIZATION> Brooklyn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodgers </ORGANIZATION>, folks -RRB- ready to do his delivery chores. On the street, <PERSON> Radio </PERSON> <PERSON> Raheem </PERSON>, a young man of few words and an intense scowl, lumbers about with a ghetto blaster the size of a minitruck forcing the world to listen to rap music. The stuttering <PERSON> Smiley </PERSON> lopes about trying to sell pictures of King and <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buggin </PERSON> <PERSON> Out </PERSON>, the local activist, grouses about how there are no blacks on the `` wall of fame,'' and yet only blacks and Hispanics frequent the pizza parlor. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s neighborhood mosaic slowly takes shape with sharp images of human character. Tensions and conflicts abound: <PERSON> Mookie </PERSON> and the young woman who gave birth to his son; <PERSON> Radio </PERSON> <PERSON> Raheem </PERSON> and the Hispanic kids; Radio <PERSON> Raheem </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sal </PERSON>; Buggin Out and <PERSON> Sal </PERSON>; <PERSON> Sal </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pino </PERSON>; <PERSON> Vito </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pino </PERSON>; <PERSON> Mookie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pino </PERSON>. It is the final confrontation between the hothead and racist <PERSON> Pino </PERSON> and <PERSON> Radio </PERSON> <PERSON> Raheem </PERSON> that culminates in the movie's violent end. <PERSON> Raheem </PERSON> is murdered by police; people on the block respond by destroying <PERSON> Sal </PERSON>'s pizzeria. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> does not set up a frenzied, random or mob-inspired reaction. Indeed, it is <PERSON> Mookie </PERSON>, a character who easily talks to everyone and who plays the role of peacekeeper, who casts the first stone. He is, as <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> X </PERSON> advised, doing whatever is necessary to fight racism. As <PERSON> Sal </PERSON>, the Italian who has run a business in a black neighborhood for 25 years, <PERSON> Aiello </PERSON> is splendid. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> is endearing as the downtrodden <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON>, and his wife, <PERSON> Ruby </PERSON> <PERSON> Dee </PERSON>, has a wonderful character in <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON>'s love interest, Mother Sister. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Torturro </PERSON> does a believable stupid punk as the racist <PERSON> Pino </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> is menacing as <PERSON> Raheem </PERSON>. The movie introduces <PERSON> Rosie </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> in the role of <PERSON> Tina </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mookie </PERSON>'s girlfriend She also does some explosive dancing with the opening titles. However, as an actress, her lines are muddled. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> has created something of a repertory company with his films, and one sees familiar faces in them all. His sister, <PERSON> Joie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, who co-starred in `` She's Got ta Have It,'' returns as <PERSON> Mookie </PERSON>'s gracious sister, <PERSON> Jade </PERSON>, who is adored by <PERSON> Sal </PERSON>. <PERSON> Giancarlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON>, who has co-starred in <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s two major releases, plays Buggin Out. <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON> has found his niche with <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>: In `` She's Got ta Have It,'' he was a nacissistic dandy; in `` School Daze,'' he was a narcissistic fraternity brother; as Buggin Out, he's self-righteous. As for <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, he has never really thought of himself as an actor. Yet, he always puts in a star performance. His direction is tight, and the mood he creates leaves one as hot as the characters on the screen. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> has a powerful movie, whose truths may repel those who continue to deny that racism is indeed woven into the fabric of American life. The 40 Acres and a Mule Filmworks production is rated R.
</TEXT>
