<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Elderly-Profile Adv29   06-26 0930</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Elderly-Profile, Adv 29,0955</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, June 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Elderly Growing in Number and Influence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When next year's head count is done <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> officials expect to report there are more people aged 65 and over than there were Americans at the time of the Civil War. The 1860 Census found 31.4 million Americans. The 1990 count is expected to find 31.6 million people 65 and older, 13.2 million of those being 75 and older. The 1830 Census counted 12.9 million people. `` There is no historical precedent for the aging of our population. We are in the midst of a new social phenomenon,'' wrote <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Soldo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Emily </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Agree </PERSON> in `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Elderly,'' a study for the private <ORGANIZATION> Population </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. `` We can not foresee all the repercussions, implications, or social changes stemming from the presence of so many older persons and the aging of society.'' People born in 1900 could expect to live 47 years. Life expectancy passed 50 in 1908, topped 60 in the 1930s and hit 70 in the'60s. Americans born today can expect to live about 75 years, thanks largely to better medical care. The elderly comprise about 12.2 percent of the population. Well over half are women, 70 percent say they're healthy and three-fourths own their homes. They also spend a greater percentage of what are often fixed incomes on food, housing and health care than younger people. But take a closer look. By definition the elderly are 65 and up, but the mix is changing. In 1960, 6.1 percent of the population was 65 to 74 and 3.1 percent was 75 and older. By 1987, 7.2 percent were 65 to 74 and 5 percent were 75 or older. A half-century ago, men and women comprised equal numbers of the elderly, but women began living longer in the 1930s as pregnancy-and childbirth-related deaths began declining. Women now live an average 78.3 years, compared with 71.5 years for men, and comprise 59.2 percent of those age 65 and over. As of 1988, 10.3 percent of all <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> males were 65 or older, compared with 14.3 percent of all women. `` The problems of old age in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> are largely the problems of women. Six out of every 10 older Americans are women,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, a former director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> on Aging. `` In general, older women have fewer financial assets and, because they typically outlive their spouses, are more dependent on adult children and formal health care services,'' Agree and <PERSON> Soldo </PERSON> wrote. And that poses a problem, with the need for home care for many elderly rising just as social change threatens to undermine the traditional source of that care, says researcher Alice T. Day. In a 1985 <ORGANIZATION> Population </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> report, she estimated 6.6 million elderly people needed long-term care but only 1.4 million were in nursing homes. The rest were helped by families. But small families mean fewer young people to care for the elderly and most of them face other obligations, including jobs. While elderly women tend to be widows, 80 percent of men aged 65 to 74 are married, as are 66 percent of those aged 75 and over. As people age, health is of increasing concern. `` Four out of every five noninstitutionalized older persons have at least one chronic condition and many have more than one,'' said <PERSON> Soldo </PERSON> and Agree. `` The most common of these diseases are arthritis, hypertension, heart disease and hearing impairments.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> reported in 1984 that 23 percent of the elderly had trouble completing at least one common task like shopping, preparing meals and housework. Nevertheless, a survey by the center found that 70 percent of elderly considered themselves to be in good or excellent health. Those with higher incomes were more likely to list themselves in excellent health. Since most elderly people are retired, they have lower average incomes. In 1986, median income for families headed by someone 65 and older was $ 19,932, about 62 percent of that for families headed by someone 25 to 64. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging in 1985 reported a median income of $ 20,354 for families with a 65 - to 74-year-old head, $ 16,412 for those headed by 75 - to 84-year-olds, and $ 15,111 for 85 and With less cash, the elderly tend to spend a bigger percentage of it on food, housing and health care than do younger people. Even so, business now views the elderly as a market segment of growing importance, and has begun targeting products and advertising. Another place where the elderly have attracted attention is the voting booth. More than one in five voters in the 1986 congressional elections was 65 and over. While 46 percent of all eligible voters went to the polls, 65.1 percent of those 65 to 74 voted, the most of any population segment. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee found that most older people are adequately housed, although some have problems finding affordable homes. In 1985, three-fourths of elder households owned their home and 25 percent rented. Males were more likely to own than were females, and those over age 75 were more likely to rent. The elderly tended to occupy older homes, 36 percent living in house built before 1940, compared to 21 percent of younger people. The 1983 Annual Housing Survey found 10 percent of the homes occupied by the elderly with some serious flaw in such areas as plumbing, electrical, structure and heating.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 29</NOTE>
