<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Gardening Adv29   06-26 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Gardening, Adv 29,0806</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, June 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part-Time Gardening Expands After Retirement</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE: <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bria </PERSON> retired from the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 after 40 years that included coverage of World War II from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BRIA</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 My garden looks tidier and yields richer harvests today than the vegetable patch I was cultivating eight years ago when, at age 65, I drew my first pension check. Leisure has worked wonders. New retirees planning to raise vegetables will enter an exciting era. The kitchen garden, reflecting our widely traveled population, has acquired a global look, with European and oriental favorites now maturing next to the old corn patch. Midget vegetables and intensive growing techniques have come along for people with small gardens. Also, power tillers as light as 17 pounds, a boon for seniors. To meet demand, new seed houses have sprung up dealing primarily in exotic fare. Old established catalogs have added international sections. If you liked a crisp lettuce you savored in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, a red radicchio chicory in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> or a bok-choi cabbage in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, you can find the seeds here. Meanwhile, domestic breeders multiplied their own offerings. All told, up to 130 new cultivars, from beans to zucchini, appeared in this year's catalogs. Why grow your own when the world's choicest produce adorns supermarket shelves? Well, anyone who has nurtured a bean or tomato from babyhood knows no store-bought veggie matches the taste of the home garden's fresh young crops. Legions of us share that feeling. A Gallup survey for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gardening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> shows 31 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> households grew vegetables in 1988. Some garden organically, avoiding pesticides. For my 70th birthday, my wife, children and grandchildren bought me a new fence to replace the unsightly sagging wire and rotting locust poles. With a post-hole digger and grunts of strength, my son put in pressure-treated poles to resist the weather. Above the taut new chicken wire we strung a battery-operated `` hot'' wire to keep out woodchuck and raccoon. Along with the facelift, I set out to deepen the scattered know-how I had accumulated in 30 years of gardening. Enrolling in a college horticulture course, I met numerous other seniors with the same intention, among them a 75-year-old whose children had given him a greenhouse for his birthday. We got valuable tips and sobering insights into the magnitude of the subject from professors discussing soil, water, sun and plants in terms of complex chemical equations. Seniors wanting a less formal approach will find wide coverage of gardening in books, magazines and newspapers, the best advice often coming from the local columnist, who knows the peculiarities of the area. Television, radio and videocassettes cover the field. Computer owners can buy software that will design gardens, plan crops according to geographical location, give tips on fertilizers, estimate costs and keep records. On my own, I dug into the often-hard-to-find history and legends of the vegetables I was raising, putting together a modest little bookshelf of intriguing lore. And, smoothly helped along by my word processor, I streamlined and greatly expanded my day-to-day notes on the progress of the season. As time went on, gardening became more and more a year-round activity for me. Indoors, under lights, I'm always growing something. In the winter, I raise lettuce, arugula, parsley, basil, chives and some small tomatoes in a custom-made fluorescent stand in the dining room. The same stand serves to start the seeds for most of my outdoor summer crops, giving me a jump on the season. We live in the country, 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, with plenty of room in my 65-by-25-foot garden for space-gobblers like corn and asparagus. But in sharply dwindled space I could still produce quantity and variety for just me and my wife. Nationwide, gardens keep getting smaller; a Gallup survey shows the typical plot dropped in 1988 to only 200 square feet. But along with the drop have come miniature vegetables and techniques for utilizing space to the utmost. Tomato plants no taller than a foot are producing small fruit in four-inch pots. I've found that three or four broccoli plants, two zucchini plants, a few tomato plants and a couple of eggplants fill our two-person needs in these crops. I grow varieties with staggered harvests and also succession crops of beans and lettuce, keeping the garden busy deep into the frosts of autumn. Cold-loving <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> sprouts, still green in the snow, provide us with garden-fresh vegetables for Christmas dinner. From the part-time gardening of my working years I've become a full-time gardener with something of a farmer's priorities. When friends grouse about a rainy forecast I'm thinking the rain is good for my lettuce.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 29</NOTE>
