<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a look at action in state legislatures on issues affecting the elderly.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Arizona</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> will `` borrow'' more than $ 51 million this year from state employee retirement funds and tax some pension benefits as part of a plan to eliminate a $ 150 million shortage in a $ 3.2 billion budget. Gov. Rose Mofford opposed using retirement funds but is expect to sign the budget-balancing package. Unions and retirees also opposed it. <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> will reduce its pension contribution for one year, then repay the funds in future years. Another $ 2.2 million would be raised by taxing any pension benefits over $ 2,500 for local, state and federal retirees. Local and state pensions are not now taxed and federal retirees are taxed on anything over $ 2,500. The change was made in part to comply with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling that all government retirees be taxed equally. Lawmakers also halved a school tax for residents of retirement communities that do not have organized school districts.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Georgia</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> is considering a special legislative session to revise the state tax on federal pensions to comply with the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling. The tax draws an $ 50 million to $ 70 million annually. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> assigned experts to study the issue and advise him on whether to eliminate the tax on federal pension benefits or start taxing those of state and local employees. He has n't said what approach he favors.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Hawaii</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Legislature this year doubled the staff of the ombudsman responsible for 6,000 residents of 38 nursing homes and 617 adult-care homes _ it authorized money for her to hire an assistant. Next year, lawmakers will be asked to tackle a tougher issue, said <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rongitsch </PERSON>, the longterm-care ombudsman. There currently is nothing in the state's laws regulating unlicensed care homes. Lawmakers also will be asked to expand the ombudsman's staff so the elderly on neighbor islands can be given more immediate service, <PERSON> Rongitsch </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Illinois</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislation before the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> could affect elderly people who drive a car, fill out a state tax return or face the possibility of physical or financial exploitation. One measure, which cleared the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and is pending in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, would require annual road tests for drivers 87 and older; those 81-86 would be tested every two years. The current requirement for testing every four years for those over 69 would be kept for those aged 75-80 but dropped for those 74 and under. A pending measure would allow 15-year prison terms for those who coerce or deceive elderly people into giving up their money. Others would allow hearsay evidence of abuse to be considered by a judge to help determine if a person over 60 was abused, and would require a judge to consider a victim's age and health when ruling on a motion for a continuance in a trial of elder abuse. Also before the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> is legislation to restore an extra $ 1,000 state tax exemption for the elderly that was effectively erased last year by federal tax law revisions.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Kansas</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The top legislative priority for elderly Kansans is expansion of the 1989 Kansas Senior Care Act, which provides $ 250,000 this year for in-home services to keep people out of nursing homes as long as possible. The act, passed this year, is `` a modest program'' that should be broadened, said <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Drew </PERSON>, director of planning for the Department of Aging. `` In-home services will be a top priority.'' Under the act, the state will develop three pilot projects for homemaker and personal care services to be expanded statewide in four years.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Michigan</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new law protects the elderly from insurance companies selling useless policies, and pending legislation is designed to protect them from exorbitant physician fees. The new law prohibits sale of Medicare supplemental insurance to anyone not covered by <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>. Pending before a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee is a plan to bar unreasonable fees by doctors serving Medicare patients. Doctors now can submit a bill to <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and accept payment based on what <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> lists as reasonable fees or bill the patient, who then files for reimbursment and would have to pay the difference. The pending measure would require doctors to go through Medicare.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Minnesota</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Written health-care declarations known as living wills will have legal status in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> beginning Aug. 1. The state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> this year passed a measure which allows adults to put in writing their preferences and instructions regarding care and treatment if they are terminally ill and not able to participate in treatment decisions. About 40 states have statutes recognizing living will declarations.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Nevada</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> has proposed a hotline for reporting abuse of the state's elderly, but lawmakers branded it meaningless and are studying how to improve on the governor's suggestion The proposal calls for a hotline operating Monday through Friday from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Raggio </PERSON> directed members to study the cost of a 24-hour hotline.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>North Dakota</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 1989 Legislature revamped the state's guardianship laws, provided more in-home services for the elderly and disabled and set up a system to investigate elder abuse, neglect and exploitation Nineteen measures directly affecting the elderly take effect in July, including legal recognition of living wills. The two-year spending cycle that starts July 1 also puts $ 5.6 million into in-home services. In revamping guardianships of the elderly, lawmakers required courts to appoint an attorney to act essentially as an ombudsman for the individual and to make proceedings accessible and understandable to impaired people, and required reports from guardians.
</TEXT>
