<HEAD>BISMARCK, N.D.: from guardians.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Ohio</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s first guardianship changes in more than 30 years, courts will be required to appoint investigators to determine competency and to notify law enforcers of suspected abuse or financial exploitation. The bill, approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and returned to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, also provides for apppointment of limited and emergency guardians, and for a competent but physically infirm person to name a conservator, a provision that sponsor Rep. <PERSON> Katherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said lets a person `` design a guardianship for his own needs.'' The bill also raises fees and requires guardians to file periodic reports.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Oregon</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Legislature has approved a bill linking auto insurance discounts for older drivers with a testing program aimed at keeping unsafe drivers older than 55 off the road. Under the bill, the state Division of Motor Vehicles will develop an accident-prevention course to help those people cope with the effects of aging on their driving ability. In addition to brushing up on laws, participants will be taught how to compensate for the loss of some of their physical skills. Insurance companies would be required to offer discounts to drivers who successfully complete the course. Drivers aged 55-70 would have to repeat the course at least every three years to keep the discount; those over 70 would have to repeat it every two years. If signed by the governor, the bill would become effective Jan. 1.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Pennsylvania</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Health-care providers would be prohibited from charging more from a Medicare patient than the Medicare-approved `` reasonable charge'' for services under a pending Medicare Overcharge Measure. <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> pays 80 percent of predetermined `` reasonable charges'' and patients are responsible for the remaining 20 percent plus any difference between the reasonable charges and a provider's actual charges. The bill would make it illegal for health-care providers to charge <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> patients more than the reasonable charge. Violators would be subject to public reprimand, orders to reimburse the patient with interest, and fines of $ 2,000 and up for second and subsequent offenses. For four or more violations, a board may refuse to renew, or may revoke or suspend a provider's license.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>South Dakota</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> have launched a campaign to provide more tax refunds to the state's low-income elderly Under the program, low-income disabled people or those older than 65 can apply for partial refunds of the sales tax or property tax they pay. At <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON>'s urging, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> in each of the past two years raised the money available for the refunds. The 1989 Legislature set aside $ 1 million and increased the income limits to $ 7,200 for individuals and $ 9,675 for families for refund applications submitted after Jan. 1, 1990. Since the program was started in 1974, state officials in most years have had trouble spending all the available money because many eligible people do n't apply. <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON> has appeared on television to urge people to apply.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Texas</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> is urging lawmakers in special session to crack down on misleading and high-pressure sales of Medigap insurance, designed to cover expenses not paid by <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>. Proposed regulations died during the regular legislative session that ended May 29 and <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wrotenbery </PERSON> asked Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> to place the issue before legislators again during the current special session. <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> gave no indication if he would put the measure on the agenda.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 29</NOTE>
