<HEAD>Blacks Seek GM Boycott Over Bias Suit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Civil rights gains will be eroded further if a federal judge approves <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed settlement of a discrimination suit, says a spokesman for a group of disgruntled black workers. The Concerned Black Salaried Employees of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> has called on the black community, including co-workers, to boycott <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> products until a settlement it believes is more equitable is reached, spokesman <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Quick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said Sunday. The group also hopes to fill a courtroom with angry workers today, when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Feikens </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> is scheduled to begin two days of hearings on <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s settlement proposal. The employee group spent the weekend rallying support for the boycott it launched Wednesday, Quick said during a telephone interview from his <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> home. He said the group has draw up to 600 people at its meetings. `` We feel that if the settlement is forced down our throats by Judge <PERSON> Feikens </PERSON>, then that will begin a new era of discrimination in this country,'' said Quick, 52, a former <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> salaried worker and plaintiff in the suit. `` We feel our days in court have been just about snuffed out because of the recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions'' involving racial issues including reverse discrimination, he said. `` Passive resistance is the approach that we must now seriously consider to make fair hiring practices a real part of good business practice in general,'' Quick said. The suit, filed in 1983 by four black salaried <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> employees, was certified for class action in 1986 on behalf of 10,000 such workers in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has offered to pay cash settlements to some workers and raise the salaries of others. But the automaker does not admit to discriminating against black workers in pay raises and promotions. If accepted, the settlement would amount to $ 20 million to $ 40 million over the next five years for the plaintiffs, their attorneys said. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> also proposes to monitor the pay and promotion of black workers for five years and to assess that information using computer models for comparable white employees. `` We continue to believe that the proposed agreement is a win-win settlement, and we will wait for the court's review'' this week, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Molloy </PERSON> said. But the settlement proposal falls short in several areas, including payment for damages or lost wages, the Concerned Black Salaried Employees said. The <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> plan would make payments only to those workers whose wages were most out of line, rather than compensate all black workers whose salary fell below the norm, the group claims. It also said the company's proposal would be less binding and enforceable than current policies under the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>. Not all of the suit's plaintiffs oppose the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> proposal. One of the original four workers who filed the suit, the Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Flint </LOCATION>, said he favors the proposed settlement.
