<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar moved higher against major currencies in calm European trading this morning as the currency resumed its upward trend. Gold moved down. `` The trend for the dollar remains bullish,'' one trader said. The dollar recovered in <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> dealings from its sell-off Friday. However, some light selling resumed after a quiet European opening. Traders cited a slight decline in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates, the perception that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy was slowing and concern about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.17 yen to a closing 140.18 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 140.11 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's rates, included: 1.9525 West German marks, up from 1.9390; 1.6780 Swiss francs, up from 1.6690; 6.6235 French francs, up from 6.5790; 2.2003 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1850; 1,414.75 Italian lire, up from 1,412.50; and 1.1947 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1910 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost $ 1.5543 to buy one pound, compared with $ 1.5675 late Friday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 374.50 a troy ounce, compared with late Friday's $ 377.75. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 375.30. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 375.40, compared with $ 370.00 late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell 42 cents to close at a bid $ 376.26. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 5.31 a troy ounce, up from Friday's $ 5.26.
