<SECOND>PM-Labor Leader, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0020,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists Union, Labor Lose an Unapologetic Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, His union's ..., to include Winpisinger's
age, that retirement began Friday and name of successor. A version moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Winpisinger </PERSON>, the unapologetic, outspoken, liberal leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, walked away quietly last week in the middle of his biggest fight. From retirement, however, the labor veteran _ once referred to as the labor movement's last angry man _ will surely be heard from again. His union's strike against <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> was nearing the four-month point as <PERSON> Winpisinger </PERSON>, 62, took leave Friday of the union he had joined 38 years ago as a high school dropout and led as president for the past 12. He was succeeded by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kourpias </PERSON>, who had been a union vice president. `` I had hoped very much to have that as a retirement present,'' <PERSON> Winpisinger </PERSON> said last week when asked whether he believed the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> would win their war with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` But the strike continues. And I'll be more than a casually interested observer for the most of the way.'' To <PERSON> Winpisinger </PERSON>, the strike against <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and the bigger battle with <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> is the manifestation of the `` anti-union animus'' of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years. `` There was n't a single employer in the country that did n't get that message loudly and clearly and tried to emulate it,'' he said. `` And we've had a wave of union-busting and everything else reminiscent of decades long ago.'' But <PERSON> Winpisinger </PERSON> believes the tide is turning, that better days for the labor movement lie ahead _ if its leaders act responsibly. `` When that power comes back, and I view it as inevitable, it has to be used more responsibly than ever before, so as to diffuse the notion that we are a special interest, that we bargain only for ourselves, that organized workers are somehow greedy by definition,'' he said. He believes a new breed of labor leaders is emerging. `` Most of them are younger, tested, battle-hardened and had to live through all this evolution and discomfort afflicted by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years,'' he said. `` We've profited from that. We learned what we had to do with our backs against the wall.'' His liberal view has prompted some to label him a socialist, and <PERSON> Winpisinger </PERSON>'s criticisms of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> defense buildup often seemed odd coming from the president of a union representing thousands of workers in defense-related industries. He blames the defense buildup for the decline of basic manufacturing and research and development in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and he labels <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> a hypocrite for making rallying cries for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry to become more competitive. `` Where the hell do you get all the brains to do that when he's already siphoned all of them into the defense complex,'' said <PERSON> Winpisinger </PERSON> His harsh words are not for Republicans alone. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, he said, needs to stop trying to imitate Republicans and return instead to its traditional base. `` We have a lot of people who are running around masquerading as Democrats who are pale imitations of the enemy,'' said <PERSON> Winpisinger </PERSON>, who nominated <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> for president at the 1988 Democratic National Convention. Who will emerge as the party's future leader? <PERSON> Winpisinger </PERSON>'s not sure. `` If the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people showed any propensity at all to elect high school dropouts president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> I'd go out and _ given the money _ I'd try it myself,'' he said with a grin, rolling a fat cigar between his fingers. Retirement will take him away from the platform the nearly million-member <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union gave him, but <PERSON> Winpinsinger </PERSON> promises speak out `` when I perceive the need and perceive that someone will listen ... I do n't intend to be invisible.'' He will freely assess others but not himself, refusing to discuss his contribution to the labor movement. Besides, <PERSON> Winpisinger </PERSON> says he has more important things to worry about. `` I have to catch up on 38 years of accumulated tasks,'' he said. `` And find out whether or not me and my wife can live under the same roof on a daily basis or what kind of adjustments I have to make to make that possible.''
</TEXT>
