<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Slide On Wet Outlook</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn and soybean futures prices were sharply lower in early trading today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> following reports of heavy rains Sunday on the western edge of the Corn Belt. Wheat futures were trading higher on rumors of new Soviet purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat and on assurances by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that grain trade with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> would continue despite international tensions. Rainfall amounts of up to 3 inches were reported in parts of <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> with smaller amounts recorded in southwestern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. `` That's supposedly going to be coming right across here, although we're not expecting anything of that amount,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gidel </PERSON>, research director with <ORGANIZATION> LIT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a commodities brokerage firm in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The corn and soybean markets also were pressured by dry conditions over the weekend in the eastern half of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, where higher-than-normal spring rainfall left some fields too wet for planting. In early trading, wheat was -LCB- cent to 2 cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.99 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 4 -LCB- cents to 8 -RCB- cents lower with July at $ 2.57 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 2 -LCB- cents to 5 cents lower with July at $ 1.50 a bushel; soybeans were 11 -LCB- cents to 20 cents lower with July at $ 7.19 -LCB- a bushel. Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .02 cent lower to .18 cent higher with August at 69.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .43 cent higher with August at 81.55 cents a pound; live hogs were .13 cent to .60 cent higher with July at 49.97 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .35 cent to .73 cent higher with July at 34.37 cents a pound. Cattle futures settled lower on Friday while pork futures were mixed.
