<SECOND>PM-European Summit, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Rejects Single European Currency, Central Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Britain concessions, disagreement
over currency, Mitterrand saying he might renege on agreement if Britain
holds up plan to unite; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> today rejected plans to create a single European currency and a central bank but pledged to accept some elements of a plan to form a united <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> market by late 1992. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, however, urged the leaders of the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> to endorse the single currency and central bank. French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, also enthusiastic about a sole currency and central bank, said he may renege on an agreement to lift controls on the movement of the French franc if <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> holds up the economic union plan. Under the plan being considered at an <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> summit in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, member states would gradually hand over economic policy-making power to the EEC. Surrendering aspects of national sovereignty is a key issue as the community heads toward dropping all trade barriers and creating the single market in 1992. `` Decisions on these matters are simply not on the current agenda,'' <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> officials quoted Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> as telling the closed-door summit meeting. `` We must stick to the practical and go for what needs to be done now.'' The leaders adjourned for lunch on the first day of the two-day summit with aides seeking to draw up a compromise position. West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> pressed the leaders to accept the plan in its entirety, said his spokesman, <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>. As part of endorsing the first stage of the plan, which would begin in July 1990, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> pledged to link the pound to the other major <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> currencies by joining the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System. But a British spokesman, who requested anonymity, said Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> would join the European Monetary system if <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 8.3 percent inflation rate was `` reduced significantly,'' other <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> countries abolish exchange controls by July 1990 and the community allows an open market in banking and financial services. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> argued that earlier membership of the currency alignment by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> could have shaken the entire system. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is the only major oil producer in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, and the pound is boosted by oil price increases, which tend to depress the other currencies. Since <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> joined last week, only <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> are outside the system. <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Solbes </PERSON>, spokesman for <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, said that despite the disagreement over monetary union, `` the atmosphere was positive in general.'' `` But we should n't be led into fooling ourselves ... We're going to have to work very hard ... There's only a slim possibility of an agreement but it is worth making the effort,'' he added. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> remained isolated on the second major issue at the meeting _ proposals for community-wide regulations guaranteeing workers' rights, including representation on company boards. Earlier, <ORGANIZATION> Lord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plumb </ORGANIZATION>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s legislature, cautioned summit leaders in an opening address that `` all these issues strike at the heart of national decision-making. `` It is not surprising that in the past, the expressions of grand aspiration have not always produced quick results,'' said Plumb, a British conservative. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, criticized within her Conservative Party for her often-combative stance toward the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, has adopted a more conciliatory tone in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, stressing <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s commitment to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Late Sunday, as the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> leaders assembled for their semiannual meeting, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> indicated that it will settle for a declaration of `` political will'' as opposed to a firm commitment on the two final stages of monetary union. `` I see possibilities that we will come to a common position,'' said <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON> <PERSON> Stavenhagen </PERSON>, a senior aide to <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>. `` But we do n't want to go into the blue. We need the political will to come to an end.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s aides discounted reports that the prime minister feels she is in a weaker position because of her party's defeat by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in elections this month for the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. The latest British opinion poll, by <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, was published Sunday and showed the Conservatives trailing Labor by 14 points. The other Common Market members are <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
