<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Stock Close Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with close.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices on <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> shrugged off further weakness in the pound to close higher Monday, paced by gains in dollar-earning stocks. But trading activity was subdued in advance of Tuesday's release of British trade figures for May. Also overshadowing the market was suspense over the outcome of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> summit meeting debate in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> on progress toward monetary union. At the close, the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index was up 12.1 points, or 0.6 percent, at 2,179.6. Volume was 369.9 million shares, down from 490.3 million shares on Friday. The market was boosted from the outset by a favorable response to Wall Street's strong gains on Friday. A lack of selling pressure maintained the positive trend, even after the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> market opened lower during the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> afternoon. There was widespread caution, however, as traders speculated that an adverse reaction by the pound to the British trade figures or to the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> summit could trigger a sharp correction in share prices. `` The performance of sterling is by far the overriding situation,'' one dealer said.
