<HEAD>Sears Will Move 6,000-Employee Merchandise Group to Chicago Suburb</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> will move its 6,000-worker merchandising hub from downtown <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to suburban <ORGANIZATION> Hoffman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estates </ORGANIZATION>, the giant retailer announced Monday in capping a bidding war between <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and the Sunbelt for the facility. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> won the contest with the aid of a $ 61 million package of incentives, which was backed by local tax incentives reportedly totaling up to $ 178 million. `` We believe this Chicagoland location will serve the best interests of our company and its shareholders for decades to come,'' Chairman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said at a morning news conference in the downtown Sears Tower. Last fall, the nation's largest retailer announced a restructuring plan that includes selling the 110-story Sears Tower _ the world's tallest building _ and shifting the <ORGANIZATION> Merchandise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> hub to less costly quarters. The announcement set off a fierce competition between <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sunbelt </ORGANIZATION> states, especially <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> offered a $ 61 million package of incentives to keep the Merchandise Group headquarters, said Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, who joined <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> at the news conference. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hedges </PERSON>, director of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA