<HEAD>Sears Move Has Sensible and Sentimental Sides</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Sears Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> has a reputation as a numbers man, and his decision to keep the <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchandise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area is backed by some persuasive figures. Local tax breaks that reportedly could total $ 178 million, for starters. But it is possible that sentimental factors also came into play as <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> and his team weighed the pros and cons of 50 potential sites before settling on <ORGANIZATION> Hoffman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estates </ORGANIZATION>, a suburb about 30 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Less than a month ago, rumors had the 6,000 employees of the retailing unit's headquarters packed up and ready to roll to <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> was also in the running. But the decision announced Monday suggests that <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' century-old <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> roots may run deeper than the Sunbelt sun could reach <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> grew up here. And <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> grew up with it. His grandfather, father, mother and two uncles all worked for the company at a rambling West Side complex that contained distribution facilities and, until the completion of <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> in 1974, the company's headquarters. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> joined <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> as a clerk in <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, in 1956, just after graduating from college, and moved to the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> headquarters as a buyer in 1959. His climb up the corporate ladder entailed a series of out-of-state assignments from 1967 until 1980, when he was brought back to <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> as head of the <ORGANIZATION> Merchandise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. In addition to the <ORGANIZATION> Merchandise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> owns the <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> group </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> and the Coldwell Banker real estate concern. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> has no great love for <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION>, the world's tallest building, which the company is selling as part of its cost-cutting plan. Nevertheless, his office will remain on the 68th floor of the 110-story skyscraper, after the retail group moves out. The relocation of the retailing headquarters will recreate for those workers the sort of working environment that <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> found so agreeable as a young <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> executive. `` When you are housed in a vertical structure, you have less people interaction than when you are in a low-rise, campus-type environment,'' he said in an interview late last year. `` You have a more cohesive organization when there's more people interaction.'' The sale of the tower may occur by the end of this year, said analyst <ORGANIZATION> Monroe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greenstein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, who said <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> insiders had told him they were in no rush to sell the building. <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON> said the decision to move the retailing group to the suburbs satisfied three major criteria. First, he said, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> will avoid major disruptions of its retailing operations, a particularly sensitive point because the company recently launched an ambitious effort to lure more consumers to its stores by offering lower prices and more brand names. Second, in addition to the 200-acre building site, the deal includes 700 acres along an expressway, including an outdoor music theater called <LOCATION> Poplar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> said the theater will continue operating and <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON> said Sear's commercialization of the remaining land will pay for the construction of the <ORGANIZATION> Merchandise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>'s new headquarters. Third, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> got all those tax breaks. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> offered a $ 61 million package of incentives. Also, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> quoted unidentified sources Monday saying the village's incentives were worth $ 178 million, although neither state nor village officials would confirm the amount. <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON> and others said <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> ruled out <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> because it would not have been a convenient destination for foreign visitors, especially <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' suppliers from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.
