<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in business-related cases: FRAUD The court made it easier to use a key anti-racketeering law in civil lawsuits against businesses accused of fraud. The court unanimously ruled that the law applies to more than what is traditionally described as organized crime. The case is H.J. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1252. STRIKERS The court agreed to set guidelines on when employers may withdraw recognition of a labor union after hiring new workers to break a strike. The court said it will hear a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration appeal of a ruling favoring an employer in a case stemming from a 1979 strike against a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> laboratory supplies company. The case is <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Curtin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matheson </PERSON>, 88-1685. LAWYER FEES The court rejected an appeal by an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> doctor ordered to pay $ 254,000 in lawyers' fees to those who successfully challenged a state abortion law. The court, consistent with a ruling by the justices last week in an airline industry bias case, let stand a lower court ruling stemming from a 1979 lawsuit challenging an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> abortion-regulating law that included criminal penalties for physicians who violated it. The case is Diamond vs. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, 88-664. AMOS ` N' ANDY The court let stand a ruling that <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> no longer enjoys trademark protection for the `` Amos ` N' Andy'' radio and television shows. The justices, without comment, refused to review a federal appeals court ruling that <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> abandoned the trademarks when, under pressure from civil rights groups, it suspended commercial use of the shows. The case is <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON>, 88-1804. PUNITIVE DAMAGES The court ruled the Constitution's ban on excessive fines places no limit on how much money can be won in personal-injury lawsuits. By a 7-2 vote, the justices refused to extend the prohibition against the excessive fines to civil as well as criminal cases. But the justices left open the possibility that the Constitution's due-process requirements could put a lid on punitive damage awards. That issue was not raised properly in the case decided today. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Browning-Ferris </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Kelco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disposal </ORGANIZATION>, 88-556.
