<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, angered by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s rejection of a single European currency and central bank, threatened Monday to renege on an agreement that forms part of the drive for a united European market by 1992. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> refused at the opening session of a two-day summit to embrace a plan for a tight monetary union of the 12 nations of the European Economic Community. Her opposition prompted French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> to threaten to renege on promises for more liberalized money markets. `` If there is no agreement ... as a totality, then countries who are committed to lifting exchange controls could be led to revise their position,'' a French spokesman quoted <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> as saying in the closed-door session. Spanish officials worked late Monday trying to win backing for a four-point compromise proposal to submit to the leaders Tuesday, the final day of the semi-annual summit. Its most controversial point seeks backing for moves to create a common central bank. The leaders had gone into the summit at odds over key parts of the plan, supported most enthusiastically by <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and opposed by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. This split surfaced in their daylong closed-door talks. `` The rough work was in the hands of President <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, who said it quite strongly, while the nuances were with'' West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>,'' said Dutch Prime Minister <PERSON> Ruud </PERSON> <PERSON> Lubbers </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> urged his colleagues to accept the far-reaching changes. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said she supported closer monetary and economic cooperation but objected to the two subsequent stages that would lead to a single central bank and a common currency in the trading bloc. `` Decisions on these matters are simply not on the current agenda,'' a British official quoted Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> as telling other leaders during the closed-door session. `` We must stick to the practical and go for what needs to be done now.'' <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> was backed at times by <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>. The moves for monetary union have added a new dimension to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s plans to fashion a single market by the end of 1992. By that date, the nations want to remove the many trade barriers that prevent the free movement of people, goods, services and money. Officials said there was general agreement the 12 nations should cooperate more in economic and monetary matters. `` We commit ourselves to the goal of the economic and monetary union process,'' said the British official. `` What we have not committed ourselves to is a process as defined in -LRB- the report -RRB-.'' As part of endorsing a first stage of the plan, which would begin in July 1990, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> pledged to link the pound to the other major <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> currencies by joining the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System. But Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> would join the system only if <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 8.3 percent inflation rate was `` reduced significantly,'' other <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> nations abolished controls on their currencies by July 1990 and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> provides for an open market in banking and financial services. Only the currencies of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> are not full members. <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> members are: <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>.
