<HEAD>Coffee Futures Sag To 11-Month Low On International Discord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Coffee futures prices sagged to an 11-month low Monday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> amid growing pessimism about the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to keep its grip on price controls. On other markets, orange juice futures soared; corn and soybean futures dropped while wheat advanced; livestock and meat futures rallied; oil futures rose; and precious metals slumped. <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, unroasted coffee settled 1.63 cents to 6.05 cents lower with the contract for delivery in July at $ 1.11 a pound, the market's lowest close since Aug. 2, 1988. The sell-off was sparked by news Friday that <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, the world's second-largest coffee producer, would move to abolish all export quotas unless members of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> approve a new price-support agreement at their meeting next Monday in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The ICO, composed of 74 major coffee-producing and consuming nations, attempts to control coffee prices by limiting the amount of coffee that each producer country may sell to the consumers. Discord among the members has led to fears that the current 6-year agreement will expire Sept. 30 without a pact to succeed it, leaving coffee prices open to free-market forces for the first time since 1963. <ORGANIZATION> ICO </ORGANIZATION> members will consider two proposals next week, one to extend the current agreement with no change in quotas and the other to extend the agreement with changes to increase the availability of mild arabica coffees, the type most in demand. `` The two proposals are expected to be voted on but both are expected to be rejected,'' said <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaul </PERSON>, a coffee-market analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Traders fear that if <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> introduces a motion to abandon all quotas, other producer countries will approve it and coffee will flood the market Orange juice futures settled at or near the 5-cents-a-pound daily limit on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> despite a lack of fresh supply-and-demand news. The market has been rising on supply concerns linked to the slow pace of the Brazilian orange harvest. Frozen concentrated orange juice settled 3.85 cents to 5 cents higher with July at $ 1.86 a pound. Corn and soybean futures fell steeply on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid rain forecasts for the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, but wheat futures finished mostly higher on signs of large Soviet purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat. Talk circulated that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had bought at least 500,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat on the open market. Wheat settled 3 -LCB- cents lower to 4 \ cents higher with July at $ 4.01 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 4 \ cents to 9 -LCB- cents lower with July at $ 2.57 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 3 -RCB- cents to 5 cents lower with July at $ 1.48 \ a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 12 cents lower with July at $ 7.31 Frozen pork-belly futures leaped on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> following Friday's monthly cold-storage report from the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which pegged belly supplies much lower than expected. Frozen pork bellies settled .90 cent to 2 cents higher with July at 35.55 cents a pound; live cattle were .15 cent lower to .73 cent higher with August at 70.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .48 cent higher with August at 81.52 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent lower to .60 cent higher with July at 49.97 cents a pound. Crude oil futures surpassed $ 20 a barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as the energy market rallied for the sixth straight day on supply fears and technical factors. West Texas Intermediate crude settled 9 cents to 54 cents higher with August at $ 20.25 a barrel; heating oil was .13 cent to .22 cent higher with July at 49.65 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .15 cent to .77 cent higher with July at 63.69 cents a gallon. Gold futures retreated on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> following strong gains last week. Analysts said a stronger dollar kept the market under pressure. Gold settled $ 3.40 to $ 4 lower with August at $ 378.30 an ounce; silver was 2.3 cents to 2.4 cents lower with July at $ 5.31 a troy ounce.
