<HEAD>Crude Prices Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Energy futures finished higher Monday, led by a surge in crude oil prices. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the August contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, broke through the $ 20 level, settling 54 cents higher at $ 20.25 a barrel. The contract had traded as low as $ 19.78 during the session. September crude rose 47 cents to close at $ 19.42 a barrel, while contracts for later delivery posted more modest gains. Among refined products, the July contract for unleaded gasoline advanced 0.77 cent to finish at 63.69 cents a gallon and heating oil rose 0.16 cent to 49.65 cents a gallon. Other contract months also finished higher. With little economic news to drive prices, analysts attributed Monday's advances mainly to technical factors and to OPEC-related news. Two separate publications reported that <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> oil output, while still above the quota set by the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, is declining. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> at a meeting earlier this month had rejected its OPEC-imposed production ceiling and set its own quota, saying it needed to exploit its massive oil reserves. `` The reports came through, the market reacted briefly but the impact was n't lasting,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiley </PERSON>, energy analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s oil minister <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khal