<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 200 people crowded into a federal courtroom Monday to protest <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed settlement of a discrimination suit. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Feikens </PERSON> told the black workers he would consider their objections to the settlement and make a decision in the case soon, said <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Quick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Concerned Black Salaried Employees of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>. The group last week called for the black community to boycott <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> products until it wins a more favorable settlement in the suit, first filed in 1983 by four salaried black <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> workers. The suit was certified in 1986 as a class action on behalf of 10,000 such workers in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. If accepted, the settlement would amount to $ 20 million to $ 40 million over the next five years for the plaintiffs, their attorneys have said. `` The proposal is grossly inadequate and calls for setting up a double-model standard to monitor black salaries versus white, which represents a problem in itself,'' said Quick, 52, of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, a former <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> personnel administrator. Quick said the automaker's proposal to monitor black workers' pay and promotion for five years and to assess that information using computer models for comparable white employees establishes a double standard. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> also has offered to pay cash settlements to some workers and raise the salaries of othes. But the automaker does not admit to discriminating against blacks in pay and promotions.
</TEXT>
