<HEAD>Ford Idles Two Plants An Extra Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that it will idle its <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> assembly plants for a third week after their normal two-week summer shutdown this year. The week of July 17 will be added to both plants' normal two-week shutdown for changeover from production of 1989 - to 1990-model automobiles, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitcoff </PERSON> said The extended shutdown resulted from a delay in obtaining parts for 1990 models with new passive restraint systems and was n't meant to reduce inventories, <PERSON> Pitcoff </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> plant employs about 2,300 hourly employees and the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> plant employs about 2,150. Both produce the popular Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable automobiles. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has about a 54-day supply of Taurus cars and a 59-day supply of Sable cars on hand, compared with a normal 65-day inventory at this time of year, <PERSON> Pitcoff </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Pitcoff </PERSON> was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in Tuesday's editions as saying that the parts delay caused the company to delay the start of 1990 production by a week at each plant. Because of the delay, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> asked its dealers to buy an extra week's worth of 1989 models. But the dealers balked because the company already had begun taking orders for the 1990 models. The dealers' reluctance prompted the company to shut the plants for an extra week.
</TEXT>
